1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,794
[SPEAKER_20]: Order!

2
00:00:00,814 --> 00:00:01,155
[SPEAKER_20]: Order!

3
00:00:01,195 --> 00:00:03,544
[SPEAKER_20]: You are an incorrigible delinquent at times.

4
00:00:05,853 --> 00:00:07,358
[SPEAKER_07]: Behave yourself, man!

5
00:00:20,180 --> 00:00:27,174
[SPEAKER_16]: So over the next 90 minutes, the leaders of the two larger parties are going to be quizzed by our audience here in York.

6
00:00:27,194 --> 00:00:28,957
[SPEAKER_16]: Now, this audience is made up like this.

7
00:00:29,057 --> 00:00:33,727
[SPEAKER_16]: Just a third say they intend to vote Conservative next week.

8
00:00:34,328 --> 00:00:36,973
[SPEAKER_16]: The same number say they're going to vote Labour.

9
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:41,465
[SPEAKER_16]: and the rest either support other parties or have yet to make up their minds.

10
00:00:42,066 --> 00:00:51,959
[SPEAKER_16]: And as ever, you can comment on all of this from home, either on Twitter, our hashtag is BBC QT, we're also on Facebook as usual, and our text number is 83981.

11
00:00:53,020 --> 00:00:55,363
[SPEAKER_16]: Push the red button on your remote to see what others are saying.

12
00:00:55,724 --> 00:01:01,611
[SPEAKER_16]: And the leaders, this is important, don't know the questions that are going to be put to them tonight.

13
00:01:01,591 --> 00:01:07,658
[SPEAKER_16]: So first to face our audience, please welcome the leader of the Conservative Party, the Prime Minister, Theresa May.

14
00:01:22,034 --> 00:01:22,874
[SPEAKER_16]: Good evening, Prime Minister.

15
00:01:22,894 --> 00:01:25,858
[SPEAKER_16]: Your first question comes from Abigail Etock, please.

16
00:01:26,979 --> 00:01:31,564
[SPEAKER_29]: Why should the public trust anything you say or any of your policies when you have a known track record

17
00:01:31,848 --> 00:01:39,192
[SPEAKER_29]: of broken promises and backtracking during your time as Home Secretary and now Prime Minister.

18
00:01:44,943 --> 00:01:45,504
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

19
00:01:45,604 --> 00:01:46,365
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you, Abigail.

20
00:01:46,606 --> 00:01:54,359
[SPEAKER_36]: And can I first of all say good evening to everybody and thank you for you coming to be an audience at this programme tonight, which is an important part of the election campaign.

21
00:01:54,840 --> 00:01:58,647
[SPEAKER_36]: Let me tell you about some of the things that I did as Home Secretary, Abigail.

22
00:01:59,108 --> 00:02:06,681
[SPEAKER_36]: I said that I would ensure that we were dealing with extremist hate breaches and I excluded more than any Home Secretary before me.

23
00:02:06,661 --> 00:02:14,634
[SPEAKER_36]: I said I would do something about stop and search because I don't think anybody should be stopped and searched on the streets of our country because of the colour of their skin.

24
00:02:15,375 --> 00:02:27,555
[SPEAKER_36]: I said I would be tough on crime and I said I would ensure our police and our security services had the powers they need to be able to do their job and I gave them those in the legislation that I put through.

25
00:02:27,535 --> 00:02:35,653
[SPEAKER_36]: And I made sure that we kept the records of criminals and terrorists on the DNA database, whereas Diane Abbott actually wants to wipe them clean.

26
00:02:35,673 --> 00:02:38,319
[SPEAKER_36]: And I don't think that's a good idea because that helps us catch criminals.

27
00:02:38,519 --> 00:02:45,034
[SPEAKER_16]: So no backtracking and no broken promises.

28
00:02:45,074 --> 00:02:46,557
[SPEAKER_16]: What were you thinking of, Abigail?

29
00:02:47,043 --> 00:02:50,228
[SPEAKER_29]: Well, you have backtracked as Prime Minister.

30
00:02:50,868 --> 00:02:57,438
[SPEAKER_29]: You backtracked when you became leader of the Conservatives and then immediately Prime Minister after the EU referendum.

31
00:02:57,999 --> 00:03:00,562
[SPEAKER_29]: You said you wouldn't call an election and you did.

32
00:03:00,602 --> 00:03:10,857
[SPEAKER_29]: And then you are here calling an election and refusing to take part in debates, refusing to answer people's questions, refusing to talk to Jeremy Corbyn.

33
00:03:11,950 --> 00:03:20,307
[SPEAKER_29]: and you've backtracked on your social care policy and your entire manifesto has holes in it and everyone else can see that.

34
00:03:25,130 --> 00:03:33,207
[SPEAKER_36]: First of all, can I just say I'm not refusing to take part in debates because I'm here answering questions from you, this audience, this evening.

35
00:03:33,547 --> 00:03:35,952
[SPEAKER_36]: And that's what I think is important in an election campaign.

36
00:03:36,313 --> 00:03:42,666
[SPEAKER_36]: It's not politicians arguing amongst each other, but actually listening and taking questions from voters.

37
00:03:42,646 --> 00:03:46,590
[SPEAKER_36]: And you mentioned about saying I wouldn't hold an election and now holding one.

38
00:03:46,930 --> 00:03:47,411
[SPEAKER_36]: You're right.

39
00:03:47,731 --> 00:03:50,414
[SPEAKER_36]: I thought we needed a period of stability when I became Prime Minister.

40
00:03:50,794 --> 00:04:09,193
[SPEAKER_36]: But what became clear to me when we went through the Article 50 process to trigger the process of leaving the European Union, to respect the will of the British people, was that other parties wanted to frustrate those Brexit negotiations and wanted to frustrate that will of the people that had been expressed in the referendum vote.

41
00:04:09,325 --> 00:04:10,366
[SPEAKER_36]: And, you know, it would have been easy.

42
00:04:10,386 --> 00:04:12,088
[SPEAKER_36]: I could have said, OK, I'm Prime Minister.

43
00:04:12,108 --> 00:04:13,610
[SPEAKER_36]: There's another couple of years going.

44
00:04:13,890 --> 00:04:16,272
[SPEAKER_36]: Why don't I just stay and hang on in the job?

45
00:04:16,292 --> 00:04:17,374
[SPEAKER_36]: But I didn't do that.

46
00:04:17,854 --> 00:04:20,117
[SPEAKER_36]: I've called an election because of Brexit.

47
00:04:20,657 --> 00:04:25,643
[SPEAKER_36]: I was willing to do that because I think this is a really important moment for our country.

48
00:04:26,083 --> 00:04:27,324
[SPEAKER_36]: We've got to get this right.

49
00:04:27,705 --> 00:04:32,650
[SPEAKER_36]: If we get it right, I'm optimistic for the British people because I believe in the British people.

50
00:04:32,850 --> 00:04:34,472
[SPEAKER_36]: But we need to get it right.

51
00:04:41,455 --> 00:04:42,899
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, the woman there.

52
00:04:43,641 --> 00:04:45,124
[SPEAKER_30]: Who is it that contested you?

53
00:04:45,325 --> 00:04:50,298
[SPEAKER_30]: Because Labour have clearly issued a whip to get people to vote for Article 50 being passed.

54
00:04:50,578 --> 00:04:57,456
[SPEAKER_30]: Besides the Lib Dems, who have kind of said that they would like another referendum, I don't understand who it is that has contested your leadership through Brexit.

55
00:04:57,925 --> 00:04:58,646
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, you're right.

56
00:04:58,726 --> 00:05:01,330
[SPEAKER_36]: We got the Article 50 legislation through Parliament.

57
00:05:01,730 --> 00:05:02,651
[SPEAKER_36]: That was important.

58
00:05:02,751 --> 00:05:06,356
[SPEAKER_36]: It's triggered the ability for us to start these negotiations.

59
00:05:06,757 --> 00:05:12,024
[SPEAKER_36]: And those negotiations, by the way, start just 11 days after Election Day next week.

60
00:05:12,044 --> 00:05:20,575
[SPEAKER_36]: So whoever comes in as Prime Minister, whoever comes in as a government has got to be ready to actually get the ball rolling and start those negotiations straight away.

61
00:05:20,555 --> 00:05:27,082
[SPEAKER_36]: But it was clear through the discussions that we had around that time that the other parties did want to frustrate us.

62
00:05:27,502 --> 00:05:29,764
[SPEAKER_36]: And you say, you talk about the Liberal Democrats.

63
00:05:29,784 --> 00:05:38,333
[SPEAKER_36]: I mean, we have a situation at the moment where if Jeremy Corbyn was to get into Number 10, he'd be being propped up by the Liberal Democrats and the Scottish Nationalists.

64
00:05:38,353 --> 00:05:42,077
[SPEAKER_36]: You'd have Diane Abbott, who can't add up, sitting around the Cabinet table.

65
00:05:42,137 --> 00:05:45,060
[SPEAKER_36]: John McDonnell, who's a Marxist.

66
00:05:45,040 --> 00:05:52,570
[SPEAKER_36]: Nicola Sturgeon who wants to break our country up and Tim Farron who wants to take us back into the EU, the direct opposite of what the British people want.

67
00:05:59,840 --> 00:06:09,819
[SPEAKER_19]: That being said, Prime Minister, one of the things that I would like to know is, secretly, do you really regret calling this election now the polls have moved against you?

68
00:06:09,859 --> 00:06:18,355
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm a Tory and I pray and hope that we win, or that you win, but you must feel a little bit of, ooh, a little bit of remorse, no?

69
00:06:18,335 --> 00:06:27,491
[SPEAKER_36]: No, I've been in politics quite a long time and I've always said at every election the only poll that matters is the one that takes place on polling day.

70
00:06:27,691 --> 00:06:37,508
[SPEAKER_36]: And I think the British people, when they're voting, everybody's casting their vote, people here and people watching and others, have a very simple choice and it is about

71
00:06:37,488 --> 00:06:44,317
[SPEAKER_36]: Who do you trust to have that leadership to take us to get the best deal for Brexit, a Brexit deal in Europe?

72
00:06:44,757 --> 00:06:55,311
[SPEAKER_36]: And who's got the will and the vision, not just to take us through Brexit, not just to get on with the job of delivering Brexit, but to take us beyond and build a better future for this country?

73
00:06:55,351 --> 00:07:02,280
[SPEAKER_16]: Were you surprised, though, that the polls have gone from a lead of 20% when you called the election, remorselessly down like that?

74
00:07:02,513 --> 00:07:05,497
[SPEAKER_36]: David, I'm never surprised at things that happen during election campaigns.

75
00:07:05,517 --> 00:07:08,720
[SPEAKER_36]: You thought you were that popular, and now you accept you're that popular.

76
00:07:08,901 --> 00:07:15,428
[SPEAKER_36]: I'm never surprised at things that happen during election campaigns, because the only poll I look at is the one that takes place on election day.

77
00:07:15,488 --> 00:07:15,709
[SPEAKER_09]: All right.

78
00:07:15,729 --> 00:07:16,109
[SPEAKER_09]: You, sir.

79
00:07:17,070 --> 00:07:20,615
[SPEAKER_09]: Just to face it, you called the election for your own political gains.

80
00:07:20,655 --> 00:07:22,717
[SPEAKER_09]: It's nothing to do with the good of the country.

81
00:07:22,737 --> 00:07:24,239
[SPEAKER_09]: It's for your own political gains.

82
00:07:24,900 --> 00:07:26,141
[SPEAKER_36]: No, it's not, sir.

83
00:07:26,181 --> 00:07:28,504
[SPEAKER_36]: Can I just say to you, as I've just said,

84
00:07:30,172 --> 00:07:39,823
[SPEAKER_36]: It would have been the easiest thing in the world for me, having become Prime Minister after the referendum when David Cameron resigned, to say, you know, the next election is not till 2020.

85
00:07:39,863 --> 00:07:43,147
[SPEAKER_36]: This is a good job.

86
00:07:43,347 --> 00:07:44,489
[SPEAKER_36]: I enjoy doing this job.

87
00:07:44,989 --> 00:07:45,530
[SPEAKER_36]: I want to do it.

88
00:07:45,550 --> 00:07:49,114
[SPEAKER_36]: In this job, I do what I believe is the best for Britain.

89
00:07:49,134 --> 00:07:52,458
[SPEAKER_36]: I could have stayed on doing that job for another couple of years and not called an election.

90
00:07:52,478 --> 00:07:53,820
[SPEAKER_09]: Your party called the European referendum.

91
00:07:53,840 --> 00:07:54,981
[SPEAKER_09]: I had the balls to call an election.

92
00:07:54,961 --> 00:07:57,389
[SPEAKER_09]: for the good of the Conservative Party.

93
00:07:57,590 --> 00:08:01,764
[SPEAKER_09]: You've called a general election for the good of the Conservative Party and it's going to backfire on you.

94
00:08:02,466 --> 00:08:03,570
[SPEAKER_36]: No, I called...

95
00:08:06,537 --> 00:08:16,992
[SPEAKER_36]: I called a general election because I believe that the British people have a right to vote and to say who they want to see leading them through the Brexit negotiations.

96
00:08:17,472 --> 00:08:24,603
[SPEAKER_36]: And I believe they should have a Prime Minister who has an absolutely resolute determination to respect their will.

97
00:08:25,384 --> 00:08:34,557
[SPEAKER_36]: My party is the only party that is going to respect the will of the British people, get on with the job and deliver a successful Brexit.

98
00:08:34,577 --> 00:08:34,857
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, come on.

99
00:08:36,338 --> 00:08:37,879
[SPEAKER_16]: We'll come on to Brexit in a moment.

100
00:08:37,899 --> 00:08:38,700
[SPEAKER_16]: One more point from you.

101
00:08:40,281 --> 00:08:48,248
[SPEAKER_39]: I think it's a very different thing to debate a studio audience as in debating the other leaders.

102
00:08:48,748 --> 00:08:51,651
[SPEAKER_39]: And I think there's been a lot of debating through the media.

103
00:08:51,731 --> 00:09:06,143
[SPEAKER_39]: Would it not give a more interesting debate having you say these things face-to-face to the other leaders and speak that way about policies rather than through TV and through journalists?

104
00:09:06,612 --> 00:09:06,973
[SPEAKER_39]: Well.

105
00:09:11,725 --> 00:09:16,612
[SPEAKER_36]: I think election campaigns should be about getting out and about.

106
00:09:17,434 --> 00:09:25,245
[SPEAKER_36]: Yes, answering questions from voters, meeting voters, talking to people across the UK in a whole variety of circumstances.

107
00:09:25,626 --> 00:09:33,998
[SPEAKER_36]: I'm afraid I think that actually having that interaction with voters is more useful for the voter and for the politician.

108
00:09:34,018 --> 00:09:39,066
[SPEAKER_36]: I think anybody who wants to be Prime Minister should be out and about, listening to what people are thinking.

109
00:09:39,046 --> 00:09:44,534
[SPEAKER_36]: And I don't think seven politicians just arguing amongst themselves is actually that interesting or that revealing.

110
00:09:44,874 --> 00:09:47,678
[SPEAKER_16]: OK. Let's... We'll go on.

111
00:09:47,718 --> 00:09:49,961
[SPEAKER_16]: I want to go on, because we've talked about the election.

112
00:09:49,981 --> 00:09:53,005
[SPEAKER_16]: Let's go on to talking about Brexit, which you've mentioned once or twice.

113
00:09:53,085 --> 00:09:55,208
[SPEAKER_16]: Barry Clark, could we have your question?

114
00:09:55,248 --> 00:09:56,250
[SPEAKER_16]: Barry Clark, please.

115
00:09:59,975 --> 00:10:00,395
[SPEAKER_08]: Good evening.

116
00:10:00,676 --> 00:10:01,156
[SPEAKER_36]: Good evening.

117
00:10:01,757 --> 00:10:07,585
[SPEAKER_08]: If the EU start being awkward, why don't we just cut and run and pay no money at all?

118
00:10:13,876 --> 00:10:17,141
[SPEAKER_36]: I've said that I think no deal would be better than a bad deal.

119
00:10:17,882 --> 00:10:26,995
[SPEAKER_36]: Now, I'm confident we can get a good deal with the right plan for those negotiations because I think a good deal is in our interest and in the interest of the rest of the EU.

120
00:10:27,376 --> 00:10:30,220
[SPEAKER_36]: But we have to be prepared to stand up for Britain.

121
00:10:30,561 --> 00:10:35,668
[SPEAKER_36]: We have to be prepared to go in there recognising that we're not willing to accept a bad deal.

122
00:10:35,708 --> 00:10:37,110
[SPEAKER_16]: What is a bad deal?

123
00:10:37,230 --> 00:10:38,312
[SPEAKER_16]: People are very confused.

124
00:10:38,332 --> 00:10:41,757
[SPEAKER_16]: You talk all the time about a bad deal which you won't accept.

125
00:10:41,737 --> 00:10:44,420
[SPEAKER_16]: explain what in your mind would be a bad deal?

126
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:52,368
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, yes, I think on the one hand, David, you've got politicians in Europe, some of whom are talking about punishing the UK for leaving the EU.

127
00:10:52,748 --> 00:10:56,072
[SPEAKER_36]: I think what they want to see in terms of that punishment would be a bad deal.

128
00:10:56,432 --> 00:11:05,061
[SPEAKER_36]: And secondly, you've got politicians here in the United Kingdom who seem to be willing to accept any deal, whatever it is, just for the sake of getting a deal.

129
00:11:05,422 --> 00:11:10,647
[SPEAKER_36]: And I think the danger is they'd be accepting the worst possible deal at the highest possible price.

130
00:11:12,567 --> 00:11:15,591
[SPEAKER_36]: Good evening.

131
00:11:16,232 --> 00:11:22,039
[SPEAKER_42]: You always say you want to serve for the whole people of Britain, but the Brexit was basically voted by 52%.

132
00:11:23,180 --> 00:11:28,487
[SPEAKER_42]: So how do you actually serve for the whole country if just 52% backed the Brexit?

133
00:11:29,168 --> 00:11:39,621
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, the first thing I would say is that as I go around and talk to people, individuals, business representatives and others, I find that actually the

134
00:11:40,546 --> 00:11:53,727
[SPEAKER_36]: greater majority of opinion here in the UK now is the decision was taken, the public were given their choice, they chose to leave the European Union, let's just have a government that gets on with it and delivers a good deal.

135
00:11:54,228 --> 00:11:59,837
[SPEAKER_36]: And how I would respond for all of those who voted to remain, and I voted to remain,

136
00:11:59,817 --> 00:12:21,166
[SPEAKER_36]: is to say that now we must make sure we get the negotiations right, we get that good free trade agreement, the continued cooperation, a deep and special partnership with the EU, but that also we take this opportunity of Brexit, new trade deals around the rest of the world, actually seeing how we can build a more prosperous, stronger and fairer Britain.

137
00:12:21,186 --> 00:12:27,394
[SPEAKER_36]: I think we can do that and I think we can do that because I believe in Britain and I believe in the British people.

138
00:12:29,028 --> 00:12:40,601
[SPEAKER_16]: It's curious because just over a year ago when you were a Remainer, and David Cameron got this wrong and he resigned, you got it wrong and remained to become Prime Minister.

139
00:12:40,641 --> 00:12:46,948
[SPEAKER_16]: You said remaining inside the European Union makes us more prosperous.

140
00:12:47,489 --> 00:12:50,893
[SPEAKER_16]: Yesterday you said Brexit makes us more prosperous.

141
00:12:51,473 --> 00:12:54,717
[SPEAKER_16]: I mean, where are you at on this?

142
00:12:54,797 --> 00:12:57,280
[SPEAKER_36]: And I set out very carefully.

143
00:12:57,260 --> 00:13:01,552
[SPEAKER_36]: before the referendum, why I believed on balance we should stay in the EU.

144
00:13:01,953 --> 00:13:04,942
[SPEAKER_36]: I also said the sky will not fall in if we leave the EU.

145
00:13:05,403 --> 00:13:12,282
[SPEAKER_36]: What then happened was the British people who had been given the choice, you know Parliament decided to say to the public it's your choice,

146
00:13:12,262 --> 00:13:13,884
[SPEAKER_36]: They chose that we should leave the EU.

147
00:13:13,904 --> 00:13:16,308
[SPEAKER_16]: But will we be less prosperous, going back to your old argument?

148
00:13:16,328 --> 00:13:21,215
[SPEAKER_36]: We've got to make sure that we can actually use the opportunities that come from Brexit.

149
00:13:21,456 --> 00:13:23,319
[SPEAKER_36]: We've got to grasp those opportunities.

150
00:13:23,719 --> 00:13:31,671
[SPEAKER_36]: But fundamentally, David, the thing I think that matters most in this is being willing to deliver on the will of the people.

151
00:13:31,651 --> 00:13:39,460
[SPEAKER_36]: not saying, oh, you got it wrong, let's have a second referendum, but saying, you voted, you've chosen, you want a government that's going to do it for you.

152
00:13:39,480 --> 00:13:45,687
[SPEAKER_36]: And I say to people, if you voted for Brexit, you need to make sure you get it with a government with me and my team who will actually deliver it for you.

153
00:13:45,867 --> 00:13:50,472
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, but the people chose, made the wrong choice by your book because you were a Remainer.

154
00:13:50,712 --> 00:13:52,815
[SPEAKER_16]: They made the wrong choice because you were a Remainer.

155
00:13:52,835 --> 00:13:54,917
[SPEAKER_16]: So in your mind, you must have thought, what are they on about?

156
00:13:55,357 --> 00:13:58,221
[SPEAKER_16]: And then you said, they'll get richer if they stay.

157
00:13:58,341 --> 00:13:59,282
[SPEAKER_16]: If they leave, they won't.

158
00:13:59,322 --> 00:14:00,443
[SPEAKER_16]: They'll be poorer.

159
00:14:00,423 --> 00:14:07,129
[SPEAKER_16]: Can you now honestly say there's no difference, we'll get richer by leaving, just the same as we would have done if we'd remained, which is what I want to...

160
00:14:07,149 --> 00:14:08,891
[SPEAKER_16]: I said that... Or is there going to be a price to pay?

161
00:14:08,911 --> 00:14:19,320
[SPEAKER_36]: I did say at the time that I thought there were advantages on balance in being in the EU, but now what I believe we must do is deliver on the will of the people, but also make sure we make a success of it.

162
00:14:19,360 --> 00:14:26,206
[SPEAKER_36]: So what I'm doing as Prime Minister is saying let's find those opportunities that will enable us to be more prosperous in the future.

163
00:14:26,326 --> 00:14:27,307
[SPEAKER_36]: Alright, too much of me.

164
00:14:27,547 --> 00:14:28,789
[SPEAKER_16]: The man over there, you sir.

165
00:14:29,029 --> 00:14:30,430
[SPEAKER_16]: And on the far side there, yes.

166
00:14:30,410 --> 00:14:32,214
[SPEAKER_31]: Good evening.

167
00:14:32,895 --> 00:14:35,862
[SPEAKER_16]: You don't need to say good evening all the time because I think we've met.

168
00:14:36,463 --> 00:14:43,418
[SPEAKER_31]: It looks increasingly likely that we are going to have to pay a divorce bill and it's speculated anything between nothing to a hundred billion.

169
00:14:44,020 --> 00:14:48,790
[SPEAKER_31]: Could you quantify in billions of pounds, straightforward question, what is a good deal?

170
00:14:49,428 --> 00:14:54,515
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, I'm not going to give you a figure on that for two reasons.

171
00:14:54,615 --> 00:15:03,868
[SPEAKER_36]: First of all, because we need to go through very carefully, as part of the negotiation, what rights and obligations the United Kingdom has.

172
00:15:04,428 --> 00:15:15,283
[SPEAKER_36]: And secondly, because if I gave you a figure here tonight for what I thought would be a good figure, that wouldn't be a very good negotiating stance when I'm sitting down, if I'm Prime Minister, in 11 days' time with the European Union.

173
00:15:15,348 --> 00:15:20,154
[SPEAKER_16]: But it is his money you're spending.

174
00:15:20,535 --> 00:15:24,179
[SPEAKER_36]: Yes, well, it's all our money that is taxpayers' money, David.

175
00:15:24,199 --> 00:15:31,548
[SPEAKER_36]: But you don't go into a negotiating stance saying, the thing I absolutely want out of this is X.

176
00:15:31,568 --> 00:15:34,792
[SPEAKER_36]: Because then you can bet your bottom dollar the other side's going to try and make sure you don't get X.

177
00:15:34,812 --> 00:15:40,039
[SPEAKER_16]: And do you think you'll have to agree that before they'll talk about all the other things, trade and all the rest of it?

178
00:15:40,019 --> 00:15:41,742
[SPEAKER_36]: Which way do you think it's going to run?

179
00:15:42,143 --> 00:15:56,070
[SPEAKER_36]: I've been very clear, as indeed has the EU, on recognising that we need to negotiate that new relationship with them, which will be about trade but will be about other things too, so like cooperation on security and criminal justice.

180
00:15:56,050 --> 00:16:00,055
[SPEAKER_36]: They want to start off by talking about the Bill.

181
00:16:00,516 --> 00:16:05,443
[SPEAKER_36]: I want one of the early discussions to be about the reciprocal arrangement for EU citizens and UK citizens.

182
00:16:05,963 --> 00:16:09,628
[SPEAKER_36]: They haven't said that we can't negotiate the trade deal until we've agreed the Bill.

183
00:16:10,029 --> 00:16:12,091
[SPEAKER_36]: What they've said is we need to make sufficient progress.

184
00:16:12,512 --> 00:16:15,796
[SPEAKER_36]: And what several of them have also said is we need to get on to the trade deal quickly.

185
00:16:16,277 --> 00:16:17,839
[SPEAKER_36]: The woman at the very back there.

186
00:16:18,038 --> 00:16:18,338
[SPEAKER_30]: Hello.

187
00:16:18,879 --> 00:16:26,510
[SPEAKER_30]: You've said that you think you can negotiate a good deal, but do you really think that you actually have any real leverage with Brussels?

188
00:16:27,411 --> 00:16:28,172
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, yes, I do.

189
00:16:28,452 --> 00:16:43,573
[SPEAKER_36]: And one of the reasons I think we can negotiate a good deal is because actually a good deal in trade terms is not just of benefit to the UK, it's of benefit to businesses in the remaining countries, remaining in the European Union.

190
00:16:43,553 --> 00:16:45,275
[SPEAKER_36]: So this isn't just about us.

191
00:16:45,896 --> 00:16:50,021
[SPEAKER_36]: It's actually about a relationship that matters to them as well as it matters to us.

192
00:16:51,704 --> 00:16:53,746
[SPEAKER_16]: You over here on the right.

193
00:16:53,766 --> 00:16:58,152
[SPEAKER_38]: I'd just like to pull you up on the comment about Diane Abbott's miscalculations that you made a few minutes ago.

194
00:16:58,592 --> 00:17:03,639
[SPEAKER_38]: Because Philip Hammond, who's the Chancellor of the Exchequer, got a 20 billion miscalculation a few weeks ago.

195
00:17:04,660 --> 00:17:05,241
[SPEAKER_38]: So I think that's a bit rude.

196
00:17:12,292 --> 00:17:23,557
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, what I will say is this, as I said earlier on, Diane Abbott wants to be Home Secretary, and she wants to wipe the records of criminals and terrorists from the DNA database.

197
00:17:24,078 --> 00:17:27,706
[SPEAKER_36]: That would mean we could catch fewer criminals and fewer terrorists.

198
00:17:27,726 --> 00:17:28,748
[SPEAKER_16]: OK, you say here.

199
00:17:29,875 --> 00:17:48,053
[SPEAKER_17]: Talk about Brexit and Remainers, I think the voting 52% to 48%, I think you would lack the confidence in asking the public, the electors, one more time, because the voting was so in the middle.

200
00:17:48,421 --> 00:17:49,602
[SPEAKER_17]: what would the electorates want to do?

201
00:17:49,642 --> 00:17:52,165
[SPEAKER_17]: I think Nigel Farage made a big mess.

202
00:17:52,526 --> 00:17:56,390
[SPEAKER_17]: I think Michael Gove led the electorate the wrong way.

203
00:17:56,710 --> 00:18:02,397
[SPEAKER_17]: And Boris Johnson, they had buses, you know, paced with NHS, 350 million.

204
00:18:02,797 --> 00:18:03,798
[SPEAKER_17]: We were all told lies.

205
00:18:04,139 --> 00:18:08,364
[SPEAKER_17]: So even people who voted out, perhaps they should be given the second chance.

206
00:18:08,384 --> 00:18:13,990
[SPEAKER_17]: So you should have the confidence to say, shall we have another vote?

207
00:18:15,691 --> 00:18:16,894
[SPEAKER_36]: Look, can I just put it like this?

208
00:18:17,114 --> 00:18:27,217
[SPEAKER_36]: Over the years in the European Union and its European economic community, there have been a number of occasions where referendums have been held in countries.

209
00:18:27,798 --> 00:18:30,865
[SPEAKER_36]: There was one in Ireland, I think France is an example as well.

210
00:18:30,845 --> 00:18:34,230
[SPEAKER_36]: where they voted against what the EU was suggesting.

211
00:18:34,850 --> 00:18:40,758
[SPEAKER_36]: And basically, the bureaucrats and the EU politicians turned around to those countries and said, you've got it wrong.

212
00:18:41,039 --> 00:18:41,820
[SPEAKER_36]: Have another vote.

213
00:18:41,860 --> 00:18:44,824
[SPEAKER_36]: We want you to come up with what we think is the right answer.

214
00:18:44,844 --> 00:18:47,087
[SPEAKER_36]: But now we know how much it's going to cost.

215
00:18:47,107 --> 00:18:48,269
[SPEAKER_36]: Sorry, you can come back in a minute.

216
00:18:48,289 --> 00:18:53,115
[SPEAKER_36]: At that time, I think collectively, people here in the UK said, you know what?

217
00:18:53,135 --> 00:18:54,297
[SPEAKER_36]: That's not the way to behave.

218
00:18:54,357 --> 00:18:58,142
[SPEAKER_36]: If the people have given their choice, let's listen to the people and actually deliver on it.

219
00:18:58,182 --> 00:19:00,345
[SPEAKER_36]: On the wrong information.

220
00:19:00,730 --> 00:19:07,499
[SPEAKER_18]: They won't give me the right information to choose from.

221
00:19:07,519 --> 00:19:08,260
[SPEAKER_16]: OK, you, sir.

222
00:19:09,341 --> 00:19:18,613
[SPEAKER_18]: Earlier this week, Prime Minister, you said that you wanted the people of Britain to trust you with regards to Brexit and winning the election.

223
00:19:19,614 --> 00:19:30,248
[SPEAKER_18]: How can the people trust you when your manifesto is not giving them any detail as to figures or what you propose to do with other things in government?

224
00:19:31,038 --> 00:19:51,578
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, what my manifesto... Well, right, I used that word trust, and I used it because that is actually what politicians, when we go out, when we ask people to vote for us, we are asking people to trust us in the role that we want to be voted into.

225
00:19:52,047 --> 00:20:05,788
[SPEAKER_36]: If I look at our manifesto, what our manifesto has done is to be open with people about the great challenges that we believe that this country faces and that need to be addressed by whoever is in government.

226
00:20:06,389 --> 00:20:07,531
[SPEAKER_36]: We've been open about that.

227
00:20:07,731 --> 00:20:14,562
[SPEAKER_36]: I've also been open that there will be some hard choices to be made in addressing those various challenges.

228
00:20:14,542 --> 00:20:17,446
[SPEAKER_36]: You talk about figures in our manifesto.

229
00:20:17,846 --> 00:20:24,835
[SPEAKER_36]: Of course, we already have budgets that have been set out in the autumn statement as government and in the spring budget.

230
00:20:25,236 --> 00:20:32,084
[SPEAKER_36]: And we've added some figures in various areas like our extra funding on the NHS and schools in the manifesto.

231
00:20:32,625 --> 00:20:42,658
[SPEAKER_36]: But I think it's important that the next government sets out for people the really big issues that are going to have to be addressed by whoever is in government.

232
00:20:42,638 --> 00:20:45,003
[SPEAKER_36]: And those are in our manifesto.

233
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:56,570
[SPEAKER_16]: The one thing that was missing from your manifesto and seemed to cause a panic in the Conservative Party was the figures on what happens to people who have to fund their care in old age.

234
00:20:56,610 --> 00:20:59,015
[SPEAKER_16]: And we have a question about it from Derek Griffin.

235
00:20:59,035 --> 00:20:59,757
[SPEAKER_16]: Let's just have that.

236
00:21:00,098 --> 00:21:01,120
[SPEAKER_16]: Mr Griffin.

237
00:21:01,100 --> 00:21:13,199
[SPEAKER_32]: I'm just wondering, with regards to social care, you kind of spend your whole life obviously working hard to build up a nest egg and have a nice little pension and savings so you can be comfortable in your later life after you've retired.

238
00:21:13,680 --> 00:21:20,911
[SPEAKER_32]: But if it's all going to be sort of taken away from you again, if your care is needed, then essentially why should you even bother in the first place?

239
00:21:21,252 --> 00:21:26,280
[SPEAKER_16]: And a reminder that your manifesto said £100,000 is all you'll be left with.

240
00:21:26,918 --> 00:21:31,704
[SPEAKER_36]: The figure that you're left with at the moment is £23,000, so we're actually quadrupling that.

241
00:21:32,405 --> 00:21:33,847
[SPEAKER_16]: You're sticking with £100,000?

242
00:21:34,108 --> 00:21:34,949
[SPEAKER_36]: If I just look at...

243
00:21:35,790 --> 00:21:36,891
[SPEAKER_16]: I thought you'd changed that.

244
00:21:37,092 --> 00:21:39,795
[SPEAKER_16]: Sorry, I thought you were going to have an upper limit.

245
00:21:39,815 --> 00:21:41,818
[SPEAKER_36]: £100,000 is a flaw, David.

246
00:21:41,918 --> 00:21:43,240
[SPEAKER_16]: There's a cap and a flaw.

247
00:21:43,260 --> 00:21:45,443
[SPEAKER_16]: But you didn't mention the cap in the manifesto.

248
00:21:45,663 --> 00:21:47,526
[SPEAKER_16]: You didn't mention it in the manifesto, that's the point.

249
00:21:47,606 --> 00:21:49,208
[SPEAKER_16]: When he's talking about the figures...

250
00:21:49,328 --> 00:21:51,110
[SPEAKER_36]: I'll answer the question I was asked, if I may.

251
00:21:51,191 --> 00:21:52,993
[SPEAKER_36]: Do it your own way.

252
00:21:58,272 --> 00:22:06,784
[SPEAKER_36]: If we look at the situation at the moment, if you need care, then if you've got more than £23,000 in savings, you have to pay for that care.

253
00:22:07,365 --> 00:22:11,471
[SPEAKER_36]: And if you need residential care, the value of your house will be taken into account.

254
00:22:11,932 --> 00:22:17,580
[SPEAKER_36]: And so it's today that we see people sometimes having to sell their house in order to pay those bills.

255
00:22:17,560 --> 00:22:26,294
[SPEAKER_36]: Now, what we say is that under the system we introduced, which is important, because we need a sustainable system for the future, given the ageing population.

256
00:22:26,314 --> 00:22:28,938
[SPEAKER_36]: If we do nothing, our social care system will collapse.

257
00:22:29,479 --> 00:22:41,998
[SPEAKER_36]: We say that we will ensure that people are able to protect more of their savings, the £100,000, that they will also not have to sell their house during their lifetime to pay for their care bills.

258
00:22:41,978 --> 00:22:46,787
[SPEAKER_36]: But I also wanted a system that was fair across the generations, and I believe this is too.

259
00:22:47,388 --> 00:22:49,993
[SPEAKER_36]: We said in our manifesto we'd consult on the details.

260
00:22:50,794 --> 00:23:05,421
[SPEAKER_36]: I heard the scaremongering that came out after our manifesto was published, and I set out one of the details, aspects, that would have been in the consultation, which is about having a cap on the absolute level.

261
00:23:05,401 --> 00:23:06,923
[SPEAKER_36]: So there's a floor of 100,000.

262
00:23:06,963 --> 00:23:08,204
[SPEAKER_36]: You can protect 100,000.

263
00:23:08,224 --> 00:23:13,951
[SPEAKER_36]: And we'll consult on what should be the cap of the absolute cap on the level of care costs people have to pay.

264
00:23:13,971 --> 00:23:17,175
[SPEAKER_16]: It's a funny thing to leave out the cap, because it's rather important for people.

265
00:23:17,796 --> 00:23:27,007
[SPEAKER_16]: 100,000 pounds that you keep, but whether you get rid of half a million or 250,000 or that, the manifesto told you nothing.

266
00:23:27,047 --> 00:23:29,369
[SPEAKER_16]: And then you suddenly said, oh, there'll be a cap.

267
00:23:29,390 --> 00:23:30,951
[SPEAKER_16]: We won't charge you more than a certain amount.

268
00:23:30,971 --> 00:23:32,353
[SPEAKER_16]: Odd to leave that out, wasn't it?

269
00:23:32,333 --> 00:23:51,439
[SPEAKER_36]: No, we set out the principles in our manifesto, which are the ones that I've just set out in the answer, which is crucially that it's fair across the generations, that we enable people to have the knowledge and the comfort of knowing they won't have to sell their house in their lifetime to pay for their care bills.

270
00:23:51,419 --> 00:23:55,645
[SPEAKER_32]: Just from a personal perspective, you're saying about the caps.

271
00:23:56,185 --> 00:23:59,530
[SPEAKER_32]: Myself and my wife, for instance, we are actually both disabled.

272
00:23:59,590 --> 00:24:04,897
[SPEAKER_32]: So I guess statistically, as we get older, we are maybe more likely to be the ones that are needing to use that care.

273
00:24:05,297 --> 00:24:17,173
[SPEAKER_32]: So are there any kind of safeguards or guarantees or something that we're not going to be left bankrupt in our retirement, basically, just purely because of a condition that we have no control over?

274
00:24:22,756 --> 00:24:30,690
[SPEAKER_36]: What I want to do in relation to the details of the policy, how it actually works, including the level of the cap, is to consult.

275
00:24:30,770 --> 00:24:39,284
[SPEAKER_36]: Consult with people, consult with voters, also consult with organisations, charities and others, working with older people, so that we ensure that we get that right.

276
00:24:39,304 --> 00:24:43,551
[SPEAKER_36]: And I think that's a fair way to do it, rather than just producing a figure now.

277
00:24:43,612 --> 00:24:45,815
[SPEAKER_36]: I think it's important to have that consultation.

278
00:24:46,376 --> 00:24:46,857
[SPEAKER_10]: You, sir.

279
00:24:48,980 --> 00:24:52,905
[SPEAKER_10]: If you can tell us what the flaw is now, why can't you tell us the cap?

280
00:24:53,726 --> 00:25:02,558
[SPEAKER_36]: Because we're talking about two different things, aren't we?

281
00:25:02,959 --> 00:25:08,626
[SPEAKER_36]: On the flaw, I think it's important that we give people the protection of their savings, which is greater than it is today.

282
00:25:08,967 --> 00:25:11,010
[SPEAKER_36]: That's why we've set that figure at 100,000.

283
00:25:11,530 --> 00:25:18,700
[SPEAKER_36]: But on the cap, as to where you set that figure as to the absolute figure that people pay, amount that people pay, I think it's right that we

284
00:25:18,680 --> 00:25:20,243
[SPEAKER_36]: have that consultation.

285
00:25:20,343 --> 00:25:27,656
[SPEAKER_36]: We will consult, as I've just said to Barry, with individuals but also with organisations that deal with these issues.

286
00:25:28,097 --> 00:25:31,903
[SPEAKER_36]: Charities that work with older people to make sure that we get that at the right level.

287
00:25:35,049 --> 00:25:38,896
[SPEAKER_10]: We had a cap a couple of years ago of 79,000.

288
00:25:38,916 --> 00:25:41,380
[SPEAKER_10]: Why can't we at least start with something around that figure?

289
00:25:41,360 --> 00:25:46,972
[SPEAKER_36]: In our manifesto we said we weren't following the Andrew Dilnot proposals.

290
00:25:47,332 --> 00:25:51,461
[SPEAKER_36]: We weren't going to follow those Andrew Dilnot proposals and there were two reasons why.

291
00:25:51,762 --> 00:26:01,562
[SPEAKER_36]: The first is that those tended to protect people who were wealthier but didn't protect people who were on modest incomes and secondly it required payment out of taxation.

292
00:26:01,542 --> 00:26:17,162
[SPEAKER_36]: And I actually think that if you're going to be fair across the generations, then we don't ask young people to be having their taxes increased in order to pay for the social care costs of people who may be sitting on a very significant value in their house.

293
00:26:20,006 --> 00:26:22,008
[SPEAKER_16]: Victoria Davies.

294
00:26:22,629 --> 00:26:30,199
[SPEAKER_02]: Working as a nurse for 26 years, do the Tories expect our support in the light of another 1% pay increase?

295
00:26:32,322 --> 00:26:32,683
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

296
00:26:38,313 --> 00:26:55,563
[SPEAKER_36]: What we're looking at in terms of the National Health Service and ensuring that we can provide the National Health Service in the future is, if we just look at how much money is now being spent on the NHS, in the five years to 2020 we will be spending half a trillion pounds on the National Health Service.

297
00:26:55,983 --> 00:27:02,835
[SPEAKER_36]: Now we're putting more money in at the moment and we will continue to put more money in into the future, into the NHS.

298
00:27:02,815 --> 00:27:09,730
[SPEAKER_36]: But it is important that we recognise, as you will know as a nurse, the demands on the NHS are increasing all the time.

299
00:27:10,231 --> 00:27:13,538
[SPEAKER_36]: We recognise the work that the NHS staff do.

300
00:27:13,578 --> 00:27:16,504
[SPEAKER_36]: But nurses get paid less and less.

301
00:27:16,957 --> 00:27:22,005
[SPEAKER_36]: Nurses get an increase, and obviously there are some other payments as well.

302
00:27:22,045 --> 00:27:27,233
[SPEAKER_09]: We've had a real terms decrease of 14% since 2010.

303
00:27:27,253 --> 00:27:29,977
[SPEAKER_09]: So don't tell us we're getting a pay rise.

304
00:27:30,237 --> 00:27:31,719
[SPEAKER_16]: Let the person next to you say it.

305
00:27:31,740 --> 00:27:32,601
[SPEAKER_02]: The nurse said it.

306
00:27:32,621 --> 00:27:33,502
[SPEAKER_02]: I agree with that.

307
00:27:33,522 --> 00:27:38,109
[SPEAKER_02]: My wage slips from 2009 reflect exactly what I'm earning today.

308
00:27:38,630 --> 00:27:42,576
[SPEAKER_02]: So how can that be fair in light of the job that we actually do?

309
00:27:42,843 --> 00:27:44,605
[SPEAKER_36]: And I recognise the job that you do.

310
00:27:45,005 --> 00:27:47,247
[SPEAKER_02]: But then why hasn't it changed before now then?

311
00:27:47,267 --> 00:27:53,233
[SPEAKER_36]: We have had to take some hard choices across the public sector in relation to public sector pay restraint.

312
00:27:53,673 --> 00:28:01,580
[SPEAKER_36]: We did that because of the decisions we had to take to bring public spending under control, because it wasn't under control under the last Labour government.

313
00:28:02,221 --> 00:28:12,090
[SPEAKER_36]: And I'm being honest with you in terms of saying that we will put more money into the NHS, but there isn't a magic money tree that we can shake that suddenly provides for everything that people want.

314
00:28:12,357 --> 00:28:17,129
[SPEAKER_33]: You come in on this.

315
00:28:17,209 --> 00:28:28,898
[SPEAKER_33]: You say you cut in NHS spending but you also cut tax for the rich.

316
00:28:32,118 --> 00:28:43,936
[SPEAKER_36]: We're not actually cutting NHS spending, we're putting in fact record levels of funding overall into the National Health Service and we will continue to increase the funding for the National Health Service in government.

317
00:28:44,337 --> 00:28:50,767
[SPEAKER_33]: But other countries spend way more on their health service than we do, but we're giving it out for free.

318
00:28:51,308 --> 00:28:54,092
[SPEAKER_33]: So why are we spending less?

319
00:28:54,325 --> 00:29:01,580
[SPEAKER_36]: Well it's not, I mean the figures do vary, but actually it's not the case that all other countries are spending more money on their NHS than we are.

320
00:29:01,880 --> 00:29:04,265
[SPEAKER_36]: We are putting more funding into the NHS.

321
00:29:04,285 --> 00:29:06,610
[SPEAKER_36]: We're putting, and we will continue to do that.

322
00:29:06,971 --> 00:29:10,157
[SPEAKER_36]: But I also want to do some other things in relation to the NHS.

323
00:29:10,137 --> 00:29:17,765
[SPEAKER_36]: We have put into a requirement that mental health should be given parity of esteem with physical health in the NHS.

324
00:29:18,186 --> 00:29:21,670
[SPEAKER_36]: I think more money is going into it, but there's more for us to do.

325
00:29:21,750 --> 00:29:26,435
[SPEAKER_36]: And in our manifesto, we've set out a whole package of what we can do on mental health.

326
00:29:26,816 --> 00:29:30,400
[SPEAKER_36]: It's not just about the money that's going into the NHS, which will increase.

327
00:29:30,840 --> 00:29:34,404
[SPEAKER_36]: It's about ensuring that we're dealing and addressing the issues we need to.

328
00:29:34,424 --> 00:29:39,790
[SPEAKER_36]: And I think mental health is something that's been put to one side for too long and not being given the attention it deserves.

329
00:29:39,770 --> 00:29:48,925
[SPEAKER_16]: Going back to the nurses, just for a moment, do you think it's fair that the nurses get just a 1% increase year in, year out, regardless of inflation, so they get poorer?

330
00:29:48,945 --> 00:29:51,569
[SPEAKER_16]: So some of them, we're told, go to food banks.

331
00:29:51,669 --> 00:29:52,430
[SPEAKER_36]: Is that fair?

332
00:29:52,470 --> 00:29:55,315
[SPEAKER_36]: Do you feel, do you sleep happy at that?

333
00:29:55,582 --> 00:29:59,430
[SPEAKER_36]: The public sector has been restrained in its pay to 1% increase.

334
00:29:59,850 --> 00:30:09,089
[SPEAKER_36]: Of course there will be those working within the NHS, nurses and others who will get progression pay increases as well as their 1%.

335
00:30:09,169 --> 00:30:12,375
[SPEAKER_16]: But are they not a special case compared with other

336
00:30:12,355 --> 00:30:28,204
[SPEAKER_36]: People in the public sector across all sorts of services are working very hard on some jobs that we want them to do because they are about looking after us, about protecting us, about caring for us.

337
00:30:28,184 --> 00:30:30,828
[SPEAKER_36]: But we have to look at public sector spending.

338
00:30:31,229 --> 00:30:34,233
[SPEAKER_36]: We have to make sure that we're managing our money carefully.

339
00:30:34,674 --> 00:30:41,043
[SPEAKER_36]: Because at the end of the day, as I say, there isn't a magic money tree that suddenly delivers all the money that everybody wants for the spending everybody wants.

340
00:30:41,364 --> 00:30:45,370
[SPEAKER_36]: You may hear later on that you can ask for anything that you want to have money spent on.

341
00:30:45,610 --> 00:30:46,852
[SPEAKER_36]: But actually, you can't.

342
00:30:47,152 --> 00:30:47,713
[SPEAKER_36]: It's not there.

343
00:30:47,874 --> 00:30:51,739
[SPEAKER_36]: We have to ensure we manage your money, taxpayers' money, carefully.

344
00:30:51,880 --> 00:30:55,545
[SPEAKER_16]: There are a lot of hands up.

345
00:30:55,565 --> 00:30:56,166
[SPEAKER_16]: So I'll go to you, sir, first.

346
00:30:57,023 --> 00:30:58,465
[SPEAKER_07]: You mentioned mental health there.

347
00:30:59,086 --> 00:31:05,515
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm just wondering, does that include the work capability assessment with the mental health as well?

348
00:31:06,236 --> 00:31:09,361
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I've just recently failed that assessment.

349
00:31:09,381 --> 00:31:10,342
[SPEAKER_37]: So have I.

350
00:31:10,363 --> 00:31:11,845
[SPEAKER_07]: Just cut through mental health.

351
00:31:12,906 --> 00:31:14,769
[SPEAKER_07]: There's a number of things he wants to say.

352
00:31:15,069 --> 00:31:16,211
[SPEAKER_16]: You say your bit too.

353
00:31:16,231 --> 00:31:17,633
[SPEAKER_16]: You're sitting together by chance?

354
00:31:17,753 --> 00:31:18,454
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, by chance.

355
00:31:18,534 --> 00:31:20,297
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay, well say what you were going to say then, go on.

356
00:31:20,615 --> 00:31:23,619
[SPEAKER_37]: Well, basically, again, on mental health, I agree.

357
00:31:23,800 --> 00:31:24,601
[SPEAKER_37]: It's so important.

358
00:31:24,621 --> 00:31:27,805
[SPEAKER_37]: The NHS is an absolute shambles for mental health at the moment.

359
00:31:28,206 --> 00:31:33,854
[SPEAKER_37]: I applied for NHS counselling about, I think, probably the end of 2015.

360
00:31:34,615 --> 00:31:36,698
[SPEAKER_37]: My first appointment is next Tuesday.

361
00:31:36,778 --> 00:31:38,921
[SPEAKER_37]: My next appointment is next Tuesday.

362
00:31:38,961 --> 00:31:46,232
[SPEAKER_37]: I've been waiting a year and a half for this, and I have suffered so much over that year, in part because of the work capability assessment.

363
00:31:48,074 --> 00:31:48,495
And I can tell you...

364
00:31:49,707 --> 00:31:54,153
[SPEAKER_37]: Let me tell you, I am partially sighted, as well.

365
00:31:54,193 --> 00:31:55,074
[SPEAKER_37]: I'm partially sighted.

366
00:31:55,255 --> 00:31:59,721
[SPEAKER_37]: I have mental health problems, and also I have other issues, so a jaw issue.

367
00:32:00,101 --> 00:32:10,276
[SPEAKER_37]: And I went into my assessment, and I was asked in detail about suicide attempts, and I came out crying because I was so upset because of the way I was treated by that nurse.

368
00:32:10,736 --> 00:32:12,178
[SPEAKER_37]: And she came out after me.

369
00:32:12,238 --> 00:32:14,522
[SPEAKER_37]: She'd forgotten to measure my eyesight.

370
00:32:14,862 --> 00:32:16,004
[SPEAKER_37]: I'm partially sighted.

371
00:32:16,364 --> 00:32:19,208
[SPEAKER_37]: She found time to just...

372
00:32:19,188 --> 00:32:23,774
[SPEAKER_37]: you know, insult me basically by asking for all these upsetting details that I cried.

373
00:32:23,834 --> 00:32:24,835
[SPEAKER_36]: Let the Prime Minister answer.

374
00:32:24,935 --> 00:32:28,760
[SPEAKER_36]: Look, I'm not going to make any excuses for the experience that you've had.

375
00:32:29,181 --> 00:32:33,026
[SPEAKER_36]: That's why I think it is so important that we actually, we do deal with mental health.

376
00:32:33,126 --> 00:32:35,529
[SPEAKER_36]: Now both of you have raised two different issues.

377
00:32:35,709 --> 00:32:41,337
[SPEAKER_36]: One is how we deal with mental health issues in the health service and the other is actually the work capability assessment.

378
00:32:41,817 --> 00:32:46,123
[SPEAKER_36]: And this is something where we are, we do look at improving

379
00:32:46,103 --> 00:32:48,245
[SPEAKER_36]: how that assessment is taking place.

380
00:32:48,285 --> 00:32:57,474
[SPEAKER_36]: But I know that the issue of mental health is a particularly difficult one to address in terms of those work capability assessments.

381
00:32:58,095 --> 00:33:11,048
[SPEAKER_36]: On the National Health Service and the other things we want to do with mental health, one of the things I want to do is ensure that there is better support in schools so that we have individual members of staff trained in schools who are able to

382
00:33:11,028 --> 00:33:15,354
[SPEAKER_36]: better identify mental health problems and then know how to address them.

383
00:33:15,915 --> 00:33:26,210
[SPEAKER_36]: I was talking to a young woman only at the turn of the year who, in school, said nobody had really known what to be able to do because of her mental health problems.

384
00:33:26,570 --> 00:33:27,812
[SPEAKER_36]: So she'd suffered as a result.

385
00:33:27,852 --> 00:33:33,981
[SPEAKER_36]: If we can give people the support they need at an earlier stage, it's better for everybody.

386
00:33:33,961 --> 00:33:43,313
[SPEAKER_16]: As I say, I make no excuses for the experience that you had.

387
00:33:43,478 --> 00:33:54,918
[SPEAKER_01]: I think it's fair to say that mental health funding is one of your soundbites whenever people ask you about the NHS, but it really concerned me a couple of weeks ago you were filmed when a lady challenged you about her benefits for learning difficulties.

388
00:33:55,359 --> 00:34:08,001
[SPEAKER_01]: You turned around and gave an answer about mental health funding and it really concerned me that the Prime Minister and potential future Prime Minister of the UK apparently doesn't understand the difference between a learning disability and a mental health condition.

389
00:34:11,423 --> 00:34:18,220
[SPEAKER_36]: In fact, when the lady first spoke to me, she talked about learning disabilities and mental health, and she'd actually raised mental health herself.

390
00:34:18,240 --> 00:34:22,330
[SPEAKER_36]: But I recognise that the particular issue that she had was about learning disabilities.

391
00:34:22,550 --> 00:34:29,247
[SPEAKER_36]: But look, both of these are areas where we need to ensure that we've got the ability for people's

392
00:34:29,227 --> 00:34:35,056
[SPEAKER_36]: needs to be identified at as early a stage as possible and then the support goes in.

393
00:34:35,256 --> 00:34:48,236
[SPEAKER_36]: Obviously all the evidence is the earlier you can get that support to somebody, the earlier you can identify an issue, then the better it is for that individual but also the better it will be for the rest of their lives.

394
00:34:48,256 --> 00:34:48,957
[SPEAKER_36]: That's why

395
00:34:48,937 --> 00:34:55,385
[SPEAKER_36]: on the mental health front, as I say, I'm so keen to ensure that we get more support in terms of training in schools.

396
00:34:55,685 --> 00:35:04,977
[SPEAKER_36]: There are other things I want to do as well, but including in the workplace, actually, because too often I think there is discrimination in relation to mental health in the workplace.

397
00:35:05,338 --> 00:35:16,952
[SPEAKER_36]: So I want to – I'm going to bring in a new Mental Health Act, scrap the old Mental Health Act, but also change the equalities legislation so that discrimination on mental health will not be possible in the workplace.

398
00:35:16,932 --> 00:35:19,077
[SPEAKER_16]: Robert Waite, let's have your question.

399
00:35:20,341 --> 00:35:27,920
[SPEAKER_20]: I will be voting Tory, but I'm not happy with the foreign aid budget and especially why we're giving money to North Korea.

400
00:35:28,361 --> 00:35:30,807
[SPEAKER_20]: Can you explain that, please?

401
00:35:36,170 --> 00:35:41,156
[SPEAKER_36]: I think the commitment we've given on the foreign aid budget is an important one.

402
00:35:41,576 --> 00:35:43,839
[SPEAKER_36]: And I think it's an important one for two reasons.

403
00:35:43,939 --> 00:35:52,169
[SPEAKER_36]: First of all, we are one of the, we're the fastest growing, second fastest growing economy in the G7 last year.

404
00:35:52,550 --> 00:35:54,672
[SPEAKER_36]: We are one of the most significant economies in the world.

405
00:35:55,093 --> 00:36:03,102
[SPEAKER_36]: I think it's right that we say that we help those people who are less well off than we are in those developing countries.

406
00:36:03,643 --> 00:36:05,485
[SPEAKER_36]: There are millions of children

407
00:36:05,465 --> 00:36:12,015
[SPEAKER_36]: millions of girls being educated today who would not be educated were it not for the foreign aid money that we're giving.

408
00:36:12,776 --> 00:36:22,630
[SPEAKER_36]: But it's also about something else, because it means that in certain states it's possible to help to develop the economy, the governance of that state,

409
00:36:22,610 --> 00:36:28,036
[SPEAKER_36]: And that is of benefit to us in protecting us as a United Kingdom for a whole range of reasons.

410
00:36:28,497 --> 00:36:35,485
[SPEAKER_36]: If we can stabilise certain countries, then that's going to be better for us, both in terms of security, for example.

411
00:36:35,905 --> 00:36:40,811
[SPEAKER_36]: But we do look very carefully at individual countries and individual payments.

412
00:36:41,111 --> 00:36:41,852
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, but North Korea.

413
00:36:43,814 --> 00:36:47,098
[SPEAKER_20]: That is one of the worst places going, surely.

414
00:36:47,483 --> 00:36:56,556
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, it's certainly not somewhere that I would suggest that is somewhere that one holds up as a paragon of virtue.

415
00:36:56,616 --> 00:37:08,293
[SPEAKER_36]: I think what the DPRK, what North Korea has been doing in terms of its missiles and its nuclear situation and, you know, we had another ballistic missile test only a few days ago.

416
00:37:08,273 --> 00:37:12,183
[SPEAKER_36]: We're very clear that we want to see those changes in North Korea.

417
00:37:12,203 --> 00:37:14,870
[SPEAKER_36]: I think it's important for China to be influencing those.

418
00:37:14,930 --> 00:37:16,474
[SPEAKER_16]: Does the aid budget go to North Korea?

419
00:37:16,654 --> 00:37:19,822
[SPEAKER_16]: Does North Korea receive money from the aid budget from the UK?

420
00:37:19,842 --> 00:37:21,887
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, the gentleman has suggested that it is.

421
00:37:21,967 --> 00:37:25,877
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't know the details of that.

422
00:37:26,735 --> 00:37:28,077
[SPEAKER_16]: Four million pounds?

423
00:37:28,217 --> 00:37:28,317
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah.

424
00:37:28,337 --> 00:37:31,862
[SPEAKER_16]: OK. You, sir, in the red and white checked shirt.

425
00:37:31,882 --> 00:37:39,232
[SPEAKER_12]: So you're the Prime Minister of the country and you don't know where that foreign aid is going to, whether it's going to the government or it's actually going to benefit its people?

426
00:37:39,572 --> 00:37:42,256
[SPEAKER_36]: Well, if we are putting money into...

427
00:37:42,316 --> 00:37:47,183
[SPEAKER_36]: When we put money into countries, we change the way that we spend the foreign aid budget.

428
00:37:47,503 --> 00:37:51,949
[SPEAKER_36]: In the past, foreign aid budget was all too often just given to governments.

429
00:37:51,929 --> 00:37:55,112
[SPEAKER_36]: And you know the stories in the past of the way the money was then spent.

430
00:37:55,533 --> 00:37:57,194
[SPEAKER_36]: So we work through NGOs.

431
00:37:57,555 --> 00:38:00,397
[SPEAKER_36]: We work through organizations that are helping people.

432
00:38:00,798 --> 00:38:11,468
[SPEAKER_36]: So money that we put into countries is targeted on things like education, on health, on welfare of people, on support for the people who are the most vulnerable.

433
00:38:12,369 --> 00:38:12,850
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay.

434
00:38:12,870 --> 00:38:13,911
[SPEAKER_16]: Brief one from you, sir.

435
00:38:13,931 --> 00:38:16,834
[SPEAKER_22]: You spoke earlier of foreign aid money.

436
00:38:16,854 --> 00:38:21,058
[SPEAKER_22]: Can you explain why it is that a great deal more of our

437
00:38:22,287 --> 00:38:29,215
[SPEAKER_22]: largesse that goes to the rest of the world, is not in the form of British manufacturers, rather than of cash.

438
00:38:29,996 --> 00:38:37,984
[SPEAKER_22]: It's much easier to avoid having a field hospital pocketed than it is a few million of cash.

439
00:38:38,545 --> 00:38:49,097
[SPEAKER_22]: And it's also the case that if this money fed its way through British manufacturing and provided British jobs, there would be much less contention concerning the sums of money that are given away.

440
00:38:49,237 --> 00:38:50,979
[SPEAKER_22]: Can you answer briefly?

441
00:38:50,999 --> 00:38:51,079
Yes.

442
00:38:52,375 --> 00:38:58,266
[SPEAKER_36]: First of all, some of the money we're talking about is not about buying kit in the sense of things that will be manufactured here.

443
00:38:58,647 --> 00:39:08,325
[SPEAKER_36]: As I've just said, if you're talking about education, it's about providing the facilities where children who would not otherwise be educated are being educated.

444
00:39:08,305 --> 00:39:12,492
[SPEAKER_36]: But we do give support to countries in ways other than just the money.

445
00:39:13,173 --> 00:39:20,144
[SPEAKER_36]: So there are some countries where we are, indeed our military are working on things like field hospitals and providing those directly.

446
00:39:20,524 --> 00:39:30,360
[SPEAKER_36]: And if we want to improve British manufacturing and British manufacturing around the world, that's why I want to ensure we get good trade agreements around the whole of the world when we leave the European Union.

447
00:39:31,041 --> 00:39:33,885
[SPEAKER_36]: OK. Sally Jones, please.

448
00:39:33,905 --> 00:39:34,887
[SPEAKER_16]: Sally Jones.

449
00:39:37,853 --> 00:39:42,865
[SPEAKER_00]: State schools are underfunded and teachers are overworked.

450
00:39:43,346 --> 00:39:48,960
[SPEAKER_00]: Why are you putting money into grammar schools when state schools are beneficial to all abilities?

451
00:39:54,762 --> 00:39:57,346
[SPEAKER_16]: Just stick with the grammar schools.

452
00:39:57,366 --> 00:40:01,172
[SPEAKER_36]: Sally, what we're doing, the grammar schools will be within the state sector.

453
00:40:02,113 --> 00:40:06,520
[SPEAKER_36]: They might be free schools, they might be other types of schools.

454
00:40:06,580 --> 00:40:10,546
[SPEAKER_36]: We want a diversity of education because education is so important.

455
00:40:10,626 --> 00:40:18,238
[SPEAKER_36]: I want every youngster to get the best possible start in life and that means every youngster getting the education that is right for them.

456
00:40:18,218 --> 00:40:33,246
[SPEAKER_36]: We are actually putting more money, you said we're putting money into the possibility for grammar schools to be set up, yes, but we're also increasing the overall amount of money that goes into schools and ensuring there's a fairer distribution of that money across the country.

457
00:40:33,647 --> 00:40:35,350
[SPEAKER_36]: But I believe it's important

458
00:40:35,330 --> 00:40:43,507
[SPEAKER_36]: that if we know that there are good schools out there, at the moment we have a law that says you can't set up any more of these types of schools despite the fact that they're good.

459
00:40:43,888 --> 00:40:44,610
[SPEAKER_36]: I think that's wrong.

460
00:40:44,870 --> 00:40:55,633
[SPEAKER_36]: I think we should allow those new grammar schools to be set up so we ensure every child gets the education that's right for them and the best possible start in life.

461
00:40:56,390 --> 00:41:09,769
[SPEAKER_26]: In the school that I work in, by 2020, every single child in that school will receive £898 per year less than under a Labour government in 2020.

462
00:41:10,169 --> 00:41:14,956
[SPEAKER_26]: My question to you is, why do you care less about the children than the Labour government?

463
00:41:15,757 --> 00:41:20,203
[SPEAKER_36]: I don't care less about the children.

464
00:41:21,314 --> 00:41:22,136
[SPEAKER_26]: I don't.

465
00:41:22,276 --> 00:41:24,081
[SPEAKER_26]: £898 per child.

466
00:41:24,622 --> 00:41:28,692
[SPEAKER_16]: You're saying the per child, the per pupil spending has fallen.

467
00:41:28,812 --> 00:41:30,276
[SPEAKER_26]: Per pupil per annum by 2020.

468
00:41:30,296 --> 00:41:32,200
[SPEAKER_16]: Not the overall figure, but how much you get.

469
00:41:32,220 --> 00:41:33,223
[SPEAKER_26]: £898 per child.

470
00:41:33,303 --> 00:41:35,087
[SPEAKER_36]: OK, you made the point, let the Prime Minister answer it.

471
00:41:35,107 --> 00:41:38,395
[SPEAKER_36]: There are two things I want to do, because I do care about education.

472
00:41:38,375 --> 00:41:43,542
[SPEAKER_36]: As I've just said in response to Sally, I think it is so important for every youngster to get the best start in life.

473
00:41:43,922 --> 00:41:47,107
[SPEAKER_36]: That's why we will be putting more money overall into the schools.

474
00:41:47,487 --> 00:41:51,573
[SPEAKER_36]: We'll be ensuring the pupil premium is there for those children who are disadvantaged.

475
00:41:51,953 --> 00:41:55,638
[SPEAKER_36]: But we will also ensure that there is a fairer distribution of school funding.

476
00:41:55,658 --> 00:42:03,589
[SPEAKER_36]: Because at the moment, as you probably know, there are some schools that get twice the amount of money per pupil than other schools in other parts of the country.

477
00:42:03,569 --> 00:42:11,742
[SPEAKER_36]: I want to see a fairer system of funding and in doing that we will make sure that no school sees a budget cut when that fairer funding is introduced.

478
00:42:12,123 --> 00:42:16,170
[SPEAKER_36]: But getting a good quality education isn't just about the money going into schools.

479
00:42:16,610 --> 00:42:20,717
[SPEAKER_36]: It's about ensuring that we're encouraging people to come into the teaching profession.

480
00:42:20,697 --> 00:42:25,463
[SPEAKER_36]: So we're going to give student loan forgiveness to people who come into teaching and stay in teaching.

481
00:42:25,804 --> 00:42:27,766
[SPEAKER_36]: It's about a diversity of types of school.

482
00:42:28,046 --> 00:42:30,590
[SPEAKER_36]: So we see innovation and creativity in education.

483
00:42:30,930 --> 00:42:43,086
[SPEAKER_36]: So we genuinely can say in this country that how far you go in life depends not on where you come from or who your parents are, but it depends on your talents and your abilities and your willingness to work hard.

484
00:42:46,691 --> 00:42:47,391
[SPEAKER_16]: We've got a couple of minutes left.

485
00:42:47,412 --> 00:42:49,354
[SPEAKER_16]: Mandy Holder, Mandy Holder, let's have your question.

486
00:42:50,498 --> 00:42:59,007
[SPEAKER_06]: Why haven't you signed a letter to Donald Trump condemning his decision to pull out of the Paris climate change agreement?

487
00:43:04,471 --> 00:43:07,434
[SPEAKER_16]: Something which the presidents of Germany and France and Italy have done.

488
00:43:07,474 --> 00:43:18,167
[SPEAKER_36]: Yes, and I haven't because I actually have spoken to Donald Trump and told him that the UK believes in the Paris Agreement and that we didn't want the United States to leave the Paris Agreement.

489
00:43:18,848 --> 00:43:33,685
[SPEAKER_36]: The G7 leaders sat round the table last week and spoke to and told Donald Trump, the six of us told him that we believe the Paris Agreement was an important international agreement on climate change, that we wanted the United States to stay in it,

490
00:43:33,665 --> 00:43:36,330
[SPEAKER_36]: I spoke to him last night about this.

491
00:43:36,390 --> 00:43:37,131
[SPEAKER_06]: What did he say?

492
00:43:37,151 --> 00:43:39,355
[SPEAKER_36]: Canada and Japan haven't signed the letter either.

493
00:43:40,277 --> 00:43:41,158
[SPEAKER_36]: What did he say?

494
00:43:41,198 --> 00:43:45,926
[SPEAKER_36]: He says he's taken the decision because he thinks it's in the best interests of America.

495
00:43:46,648 --> 00:43:52,798
[SPEAKER_36]: I say that the Paris Agreement actually is important for us globally in terms of dealing with climate change.

496
00:43:52,818 --> 00:43:56,044
[SPEAKER_36]: That's why the UK supported it and it's why the UK is continuing to support it.

497
00:43:56,024 --> 00:44:00,232
[SPEAKER_16]: You're negotiating our departure from the EU.

498
00:44:00,272 --> 00:44:11,113
[SPEAKER_16]: Wouldn't it have been sensible and prudent to go along with France and Germany and Italy and sign a letter to Donald Trump instead of it being released that you just said you were disappointed by his decision?

499
00:44:11,161 --> 00:44:14,645
[SPEAKER_36]: It's not a question of whether or not we should go along with somebody else, David.

500
00:44:15,166 --> 00:44:17,208
[SPEAKER_36]: We take independent decisions as the UK.

501
00:44:17,268 --> 00:44:18,410
[SPEAKER_36]: I spoke to Donald Trump.

502
00:44:18,430 --> 00:44:21,253
[SPEAKER_36]: I've told him my views from the UK's position last week.

503
00:44:21,333 --> 00:44:23,356
[SPEAKER_36]: I told him last night what our views are.

504
00:44:23,396 --> 00:44:26,039
[SPEAKER_36]: We remain committed to the Paris Agreement.

505
00:44:26,159 --> 00:44:30,164
[SPEAKER_36]: We continue to think it's important for dealing with climate change internationally.

506
00:44:30,825 --> 00:44:33,909
[SPEAKER_16]: Well, that, I'm afraid, ends the first half of this programme.

507
00:44:33,929 --> 00:44:35,030
[SPEAKER_16]: Prime Minister, thank you very much.

508
00:44:35,150 --> 00:44:36,912
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you very much, David.

509
00:44:36,932 --> 00:44:37,132
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you.

510
00:44:37,153 --> 00:44:37,573
[SPEAKER_36]: Thank you, everybody.

511
00:44:46,598 --> 00:45:06,273
[SPEAKER_16]: And now would you please welcome the leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn.

512
00:45:06,293 --> 00:45:07,716
[SPEAKER_16]: Good evening, good evening Mr Corbyn.

513
00:45:07,836 --> 00:45:11,222
[SPEAKER_16]: Our first question to you comes from Ciaran Hepworth, please.

514
00:45:13,379 --> 00:45:18,129
[SPEAKER_38]: Why should the British public trust you and your peers to negotiate Brexit?

515
00:45:18,149 --> 00:45:21,917
[SPEAKER_16]: Why should the British public trust you and your peers to negotiate Brexit?

516
00:45:22,859 --> 00:45:24,663
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you for inviting me here tonight.

517
00:45:24,683 --> 00:45:27,830
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm very sorry this is not a debate, this is a series of questions.

518
00:45:27,930 --> 00:45:31,017
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it's a shame the Prime Minister hasn't taken part in the debate.

519
00:45:34,912 --> 00:45:37,677
[SPEAKER_14]: First, we're very clear on Brexit.

520
00:45:38,158 --> 00:45:41,926
[SPEAKER_14]: A referendum took place, a decision was reached, we're leaving the European Union.

521
00:45:42,427 --> 00:45:50,102
[SPEAKER_14]: Secondly, we will immediately legislate in office to guarantee rights of EU nationals to remain in this country.

522
00:45:50,082 --> 00:46:02,855
[SPEAKER_14]: Secondly, we will negotiate with the European Union to guarantee trade access to the European markets and protection of the conditions that we've achieved through EU membership, because it's crucial to protect our manufacturing industry.

523
00:46:03,155 --> 00:46:07,119
[SPEAKER_14]: Your point about our negotiating team, we have a great team.

524
00:46:07,439 --> 00:46:09,261
[SPEAKER_14]: We have a great team of very experienced people.

525
00:46:09,561 --> 00:46:12,605
[SPEAKER_14]: Keir Starmer is one of the leading lawyers of this country.

526
00:46:13,005 --> 00:46:20,072
[SPEAKER_14]: I think I can trust Keir Starmer with negotiations more than some other people who are undertaking those negotiations.

527
00:46:22,938 --> 00:46:34,071
[SPEAKER_16]: On Question Time last night, your International Trade Secretary Barry Gardiner said that Britain would absolutely, absolutely was his word, be poorer after leaving the EU.

528
00:46:34,091 --> 00:46:35,074
[SPEAKER_14]: Do you agree with that?

529
00:46:35,543 --> 00:46:37,407
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't think we necessarily would be poorer.

530
00:46:37,909 --> 00:46:53,907
[SPEAKER_14]: I hope that we will retain, as I said, the trade access and I hope also that we will have a Labour government that will be investing in a growing economy in this country and challenging the terrible levels of inequality that exist in this country at the same time.

531
00:46:54,562 --> 00:46:58,408
[SPEAKER_23]: David Cameron went to the EU and asked for a few concessions.

532
00:46:58,848 --> 00:47:04,857
[SPEAKER_23]: He got nothing because they knew that he would want to stay in the EU.

533
00:47:05,538 --> 00:47:13,870
[SPEAKER_23]: If the EU understands your position that no deal is a bad deal, then you've got no chance.

534
00:47:17,444 --> 00:47:22,573
[SPEAKER_14]: I've made it very clear we accept the results of the referendum and I think it's important to go from that point.

535
00:47:23,294 --> 00:47:30,467
[SPEAKER_14]: I've made the point also about the need for trade access to the European Union and there is of course an interest in that on both sides of the channel.

536
00:47:30,987 --> 00:47:35,976
[SPEAKER_14]: Most of our big manufacturing companies have supply chains here and in Europe and vice versa.

537
00:47:35,956 --> 00:47:37,458
[SPEAKER_14]: There is a mutual interest in this.

538
00:47:37,658 --> 00:47:46,671
[SPEAKER_14]: But we're not approaching these negotiations by threatening Europe with setting up some kind of low-tax haven for big corporations in this country.

539
00:47:46,871 --> 00:47:56,765
[SPEAKER_14]: We're instead saying we want to continue that trading relationship outside the European Union, but I think a sensible relationship with them is very important.

540
00:47:56,785 --> 00:48:04,275
[SPEAKER_14]: And I will approach those negotiations to build up a trust which gives us that sensible relationship in the future.

541
00:48:06,736 --> 00:48:12,139
[SPEAKER_16]: What exactly do you think the British people meant?

542
00:48:12,237 --> 00:48:16,905
[SPEAKER_16]: who voted to leave, and what do you understand by leave the EU?

543
00:48:16,945 --> 00:48:19,108
[SPEAKER_16]: What does it actually mean to you to leave the EU?

544
00:48:19,149 --> 00:48:21,633
[SPEAKER_16]: What is it that matters in that?

545
00:48:21,913 --> 00:48:31,269
[SPEAKER_14]: Leaving the European Union means we withdraw from the Treaty of Rome, we withdraw from the 1972 decision that was made by the British government at that time to join with the European Union.

546
00:48:31,329 --> 00:48:36,878
[SPEAKER_14]: It means that there is no longer a legislative authority over UK law.

547
00:48:36,858 --> 00:48:39,982
[SPEAKER_14]: within the EU or a parliamentary consent for it.

548
00:48:40,303 --> 00:48:59,069
[SPEAKER_14]: It means we have to have an independent and separate relationship with the European Union and I think we've got two years to negotiate it and I can't wait to get started to make sure that we do retain manufacturing industry and service industry jobs in Britain that are so essential to our economy and our economic growth.

549
00:48:59,089 --> 00:49:00,031
[SPEAKER_14]: Threatening will not work.

550
00:49:00,211 --> 00:49:01,633
[SPEAKER_14]: Is your aim to remain

551
00:49:03,284 --> 00:49:05,427
[SPEAKER_14]: Is your aim to remain in the single market?

552
00:49:05,447 --> 00:49:06,348
[SPEAKER_14]: Do you think that's possible?

553
00:49:06,869 --> 00:49:10,533
[SPEAKER_14]: Our aim is to have a tariff-free trade access to Europe.

554
00:49:10,573 --> 00:49:14,338
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we should put it in those terms rather than anything else at this stage.

555
00:49:14,358 --> 00:49:16,421
[SPEAKER_16]: OK. You, sir, over there on the far side.

556
00:49:17,422 --> 00:49:18,343
[SPEAKER_16]: No, the man over there.

557
00:49:18,944 --> 00:49:20,266
[SPEAKER_16]: That's it, because he's spoken already.

558
00:49:21,688 --> 00:49:22,008
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

559
00:49:22,048 --> 00:49:24,972
[SPEAKER_13]: Will you rule out

560
00:49:25,964 --> 00:49:39,417
[SPEAKER_13]: doing a deal with Nicola Sturgeon in the event of a hung parliament, because you will be negotiating, as you would expect, with the EU at that time.

561
00:49:40,747 --> 00:49:42,990
[SPEAKER_14]: We are fighting this election to win.

562
00:49:43,671 --> 00:49:50,401
[SPEAKER_14]: And we're mounting a fantastic campaign in order to get that message across of how different our society and our politics could be.

563
00:49:51,082 --> 00:49:53,566
[SPEAKER_14]: We are contesting all the constituencies.

564
00:49:53,866 --> 00:49:57,091
[SPEAKER_14]: We are not looking to do deals with anybody.

565
00:49:57,151 --> 00:49:59,575
[SPEAKER_14]: We are not forming a coalition government.

566
00:49:59,595 --> 00:50:08,728
[SPEAKER_14]: I want to form a Labour government with a majority to carry out this amazing program, which can give so much hope and opportunity to so many people.

567
00:50:10,025 --> 00:50:12,329
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

568
00:50:12,349 --> 00:50:16,477
[SPEAKER_13]: That was the answer I expected, but it wasn't the answer to my question.

569
00:50:17,419 --> 00:50:22,789
[SPEAKER_14]: Well, I thought your question was about deals, and I said no deals.

570
00:50:23,911 --> 00:50:25,174
[SPEAKER_16]: OK, I'm going to go to somebody else.

571
00:50:25,194 --> 00:50:27,578
[SPEAKER_16]: You, sir, there, in the blue shirt.

572
00:50:27,828 --> 00:50:34,117
[SPEAKER_04]: Given the absence of the European Court of Justice, how will you uphold government accountability post-Brexit?

573
00:50:34,758 --> 00:50:38,744
[SPEAKER_04]: On environmental issues, for example, air pollution, we're already breaching limits.

574
00:50:38,764 --> 00:50:41,288
[SPEAKER_04]: The European Court of Justice holds us to account.

575
00:50:41,348 --> 00:50:43,191
[SPEAKER_04]: What will happen when we leave the EU?

576
00:50:43,211 --> 00:50:48,438
[SPEAKER_14]: I want to ensure that the environmental protocols are adopted into UK law.

577
00:50:48,699 --> 00:50:50,401
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it's very important to do that.

578
00:50:50,682 --> 00:50:57,632
[SPEAKER_14]: It's also absolutely crucial for the future of all of us that we have agreements with all of Europe,

579
00:50:57,612 --> 00:51:06,784
[SPEAKER_14]: be they part of the EU or not, on air pollution, on air quality, on sea pollution and protection of our seas and our natural environment.

580
00:51:07,084 --> 00:51:08,846
[SPEAKER_14]: And I'm very determined to achieve that.

581
00:51:09,147 --> 00:51:15,255
[SPEAKER_14]: And since you raised the subject, I utterly deplore Donald Trump's decision to withdraw from the Paris climate change.

582
00:51:15,575 --> 00:51:24,126
[SPEAKER_14]: I would sign a letter with any other leader that would deplore that straight away.

583
00:51:24,950 --> 00:51:26,913
[SPEAKER_16]: Let's come home for a moment.

584
00:51:27,233 --> 00:51:28,935
[SPEAKER_16]: Steve Rudd, let's have your question please.

585
00:51:29,436 --> 00:51:33,321
[SPEAKER_24]: I run a small local business.

586
00:51:34,823 --> 00:51:38,288
[SPEAKER_24]: I'm faced with the possibility of higher corporation tax rates.

587
00:51:39,009 --> 00:51:43,515
[SPEAKER_24]: Obviously we've alluded to the uncertainty that Brexit is going to create over the next couple of years.

588
00:51:44,423 --> 00:51:46,306
[SPEAKER_24]: Today, you've talked about creating jobs.

589
00:51:47,347 --> 00:51:52,774
[SPEAKER_24]: I just wonder how I can have confidence that those jobs, well, I as a small business can create those jobs.

590
00:51:53,595 --> 00:51:55,758
[SPEAKER_14]: Well, I don't know how big your small business is.

591
00:51:55,898 --> 00:51:56,759
[SPEAKER_24]: It's a micro-business.

592
00:51:56,799 --> 00:51:58,322
[SPEAKER_24]: It's a small financial service business.

593
00:51:58,402 --> 00:51:59,864
[SPEAKER_24]: Is this big, that big?

594
00:52:00,084 --> 00:52:01,025
[SPEAKER_24]: I employ five people.

595
00:52:01,926 --> 00:52:03,188
[SPEAKER_24]: It's a small business, but it could grow.

596
00:52:03,789 --> 00:52:03,969
[SPEAKER_24]: Good.

597
00:52:04,169 --> 00:52:04,850
[SPEAKER_24]: Let's hope it does grow.

598
00:52:04,870 --> 00:52:06,352
[SPEAKER_24]: It can't grow in uncertain times.

599
00:52:06,392 --> 00:52:07,173
[SPEAKER_24]: That's the problem.

600
00:52:07,374 --> 00:52:07,934
[SPEAKER_16]: Absolutely.

601
00:52:08,034 --> 00:52:12,220
[SPEAKER_16]: Just specify again, what are your problems with the proposals that Labour's making?

602
00:52:12,402 --> 00:52:14,986
[SPEAKER_24]: Well, obviously, it's the rising corporation tax.

603
00:52:15,026 --> 00:52:18,191
[SPEAKER_24]: It's the uncertainty of Brexit and the outcome from Brexit.

604
00:52:18,591 --> 00:52:20,374
[SPEAKER_24]: It's planning ahead, basically, my problem is.

605
00:52:20,795 --> 00:52:27,625
[SPEAKER_24]: And then, obviously, we've got the personal taxation issues that create other issues further down the line.

606
00:52:27,946 --> 00:52:35,938
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm sure you recognise there are huge problems in the funding of our public services, health, education, and these have to be addressed and dealt with.

607
00:52:35,958 --> 00:52:40,485
[SPEAKER_14]: We have a fully-costed and fully-funded manifesto here, and that

608
00:52:40,600 --> 00:52:47,473
[SPEAKER_14]: will cost, yes, and we will raise corporation tax up to 26p by the end of the Parliament.

609
00:52:47,834 --> 00:52:54,046
[SPEAKER_14]: And that will be actually 2% lower than it was in 2010 and will actually be less than the G7 average.

610
00:52:54,446 --> 00:53:00,117
[SPEAKER_14]: What it will also do is not raise corporation tax for small and medium businesses by that amount.

611
00:53:00,137 --> 00:53:02,642
[SPEAKER_14]: Some will have no rise whatsoever.

612
00:53:02,622 --> 00:53:16,576
[SPEAKER_14]: And we have had very interesting and very good discussions with a lot of small businesses about their problems of accessing capital, their problems of growing because banks don't like them and are not interested in them, and the need to have an investment strategy for this country.

613
00:53:16,816 --> 00:53:30,570
[SPEAKER_14]: So on top of that, we will also be forming a national investment bank to improve infrastructure all across the country and develop new high technology industries, which I think are the future of this country.

614
00:53:30,550 --> 00:53:36,216
[SPEAKER_14]: Let the people with the skills actually develop the jobs and develop the industries in this country.

615
00:53:36,236 --> 00:53:40,560
[SPEAKER_14]: And so, yes, we are asking the very biggest corporations to pay a bit more.

616
00:53:40,800 --> 00:53:42,742
[SPEAKER_14]: But I tell you what, I think it's worth it.

617
00:53:43,063 --> 00:53:47,447
[SPEAKER_14]: It's worth it so that any young person can go to university and not leave with debt.

618
00:53:47,707 --> 00:53:53,613
[SPEAKER_14]: It's worth it to make sure school headteachers don't have to collect at the school gate in order to pay the teachers' salaries.

619
00:53:53,834 --> 00:53:58,538
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it's worth it for a better society in which everyone can achieve something.

620
00:53:59,900 --> 00:54:00,000
[SPEAKER_14]: Okay.

621
00:54:00,020 --> 00:54:00,220
[SPEAKER_14]: Well done.

622
00:54:05,178 --> 00:54:08,102
[SPEAKER_24]: Jack Rise, Jack Rise, please.

623
00:54:08,122 --> 00:54:16,655
[SPEAKER_24]: To come back to you, I'm also working, I'm linked to an accountancy firm, so we obviously deal with large businesses as well as potential clients and as existing clients.

624
00:54:17,476 --> 00:54:31,877
[SPEAKER_24]: My choice, basically, well, the choice of my clients is a Conservative government and a Labour government, and the difference, as you say, 2%, looking at on a European-wide, but it's a 9% difference between what the Conservatives are proposing for corporation tax

625
00:54:31,857 --> 00:54:46,879
[SPEAKER_14]: for larger businesses and what the Labour government is proposing.

626
00:54:46,859 --> 00:54:52,589
[SPEAKER_14]: don't look at the problems throughout our school and education system and invest in it properly.

627
00:54:52,910 --> 00:54:55,855
[SPEAKER_14]: Where are the skilled workers going to come from tomorrow?

628
00:54:56,115 --> 00:54:58,439
[SPEAKER_14]: Where are going to be the consumers of tomorrow?

629
00:54:58,459 --> 00:55:04,530
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it's time that we looked at inequality in our society and used

630
00:55:04,510 --> 00:55:09,096
[SPEAKER_14]: a public investment in order to improve services and give real chances to everybody.

631
00:55:09,457 --> 00:55:11,139
[SPEAKER_14]: Poverty is a waste.

632
00:55:11,159 --> 00:55:16,407
[SPEAKER_14]: People who can't get the education they want and the qualifications they want, we all lose.

633
00:55:16,767 --> 00:55:24,578
[SPEAKER_14]: It's a question of whether the community gets together to support everybody or we just let the rich get richer and the rest suffer.

634
00:55:30,110 --> 00:55:39,284
[SPEAKER_16]: What's the overall increase in the tax take that Labour, if it comes to power, would expect?

635
00:55:39,385 --> 00:55:42,229
[SPEAKER_16]: What kind of percentage on the current tax take?

636
00:55:42,249 --> 00:55:43,431
[SPEAKER_16]: £48 billion more.

637
00:55:43,691 --> 00:55:45,975
[SPEAKER_14]: What percentage is that of what comes in at the moment?

638
00:55:45,955 --> 00:55:49,681
[SPEAKER_14]: 48 billion more, which is quite a small proportion of the total.

639
00:55:49,861 --> 00:55:58,515
[SPEAKER_14]: The point I'm making is that what we've got here is funding of it through corporation tax, funding of it through some new taxes.

640
00:55:58,535 --> 00:56:06,707
[SPEAKER_14]: 95% of the people of this country will pay no more in tax, VAT or national insurance.

641
00:56:06,727 --> 00:56:09,752
[SPEAKER_14]: The others will be asked to pay a bit more and I think

642
00:56:09,732 --> 00:56:13,176
[SPEAKER_14]: It's the right thing to do, because it does give us a growing economy.

643
00:56:13,236 --> 00:56:19,743
[SPEAKER_16]: The figures for the country as a whole, for the economy as a whole, is it's very nearly a 10% increase in tax take by the government.

644
00:56:19,883 --> 00:56:22,326
[SPEAKER_16]: It brings me to a question from Jack Rouse, if I may.

645
00:56:22,406 --> 00:56:23,467
[SPEAKER_16]: Jack Rouse, please.

646
00:56:25,289 --> 00:56:26,210
[SPEAKER_16]: Where is Jack Rouse?

647
00:56:26,771 --> 00:56:28,132
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, speak away, speak away.

648
00:56:28,272 --> 00:56:28,673
[SPEAKER_16]: Hi, Jack.

649
00:56:29,474 --> 00:56:35,200
[SPEAKER_11]: Is Labour's manifesto a realistic wish list, or is it just a letter to Santa Claus?

650
00:56:43,887 --> 00:56:44,849
[SPEAKER_14]: I urge you to read it.

651
00:56:45,431 --> 00:56:53,690
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it is a serious and realistic document that addresses the issues that many people in this country face.

652
00:56:53,710 --> 00:56:57,539
[SPEAKER_14]: And we've been brave enough to put it out there with all the policies that are in it.

653
00:56:58,220 --> 00:57:01,187
[SPEAKER_14]: How we deal with the school funding crisis

654
00:57:01,167 --> 00:57:10,420
[SPEAKER_14]: How we make sure preschool all children, 2 to 4, get 30 hours childcare per week or opportunities for preschool, play and education.

655
00:57:10,941 --> 00:57:20,374
[SPEAKER_14]: How we bring back the educational maintenance allowance so that youngsters who would be deterred from staying on at school or going on to get A-levels or other qualifications and

656
00:57:20,354 --> 00:57:25,326
[SPEAKER_14]: that those who can get into university won't end up with debts of 50 or 60,000 at the end of it.

657
00:57:25,606 --> 00:57:29,455
[SPEAKER_14]: This is nothing unusual in many other countries in the world.

658
00:57:29,676 --> 00:57:32,362
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it's time for us to invest in our future.

659
00:57:32,382 --> 00:57:35,730
[SPEAKER_14]: The other crisis I may mention, David, is the

660
00:57:35,710 --> 00:57:39,937
[SPEAKER_14]: question of health, the question of mental health, and the question of social care.

661
00:57:40,297 --> 00:57:42,340
[SPEAKER_14]: If we don't address it, what happens?

662
00:57:42,861 --> 00:57:44,804
[SPEAKER_14]: What happens is more people suffer.

663
00:57:45,085 --> 00:57:51,775
[SPEAKER_14]: What happens is more women usually give up work to care for those who cannot be cared for because we're not putting enough money into it.

664
00:57:52,096 --> 00:57:58,887
[SPEAKER_14]: And those with a mental health crisis suffer alone and don't get the help and support that they want.

665
00:57:59,067 --> 00:58:00,469
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to

666
00:58:00,702 --> 00:58:12,419
[SPEAKER_14]: respect the needs of people, and, frankly, challenge all of us to say, if we want to live in a society that genuinely cares for all, we've got to be prepared to deal with issues of inequality and pay for it.

667
00:58:12,459 --> 00:58:13,881
[SPEAKER_14]: And I'm prepared to do that.

668
00:58:13,901 --> 00:58:15,663
[SPEAKER_11]: OK?

669
00:58:17,606 --> 00:58:18,848
[SPEAKER_11]: It's a question of funding it.

670
00:58:19,288 --> 00:58:26,018
[SPEAKER_11]: And I'm thinking of last time Labour were in government, they left a note at the Chancellor's office saying, we've no money left.

671
00:58:29,305 --> 00:58:39,539
[SPEAKER_14]: What I would say is, for the past seven years of austerity, that austerity has hit public sector workers with a 1% cap.

672
00:58:40,200 --> 00:58:42,723
[SPEAKER_14]: It has hit all our schools and public services.

673
00:58:43,204 --> 00:58:44,646
[SPEAKER_14]: It has caused a housing crisis.

674
00:58:45,147 --> 00:58:45,768
[SPEAKER_14]: And do you know what?

675
00:58:46,468 --> 00:58:49,052
[SPEAKER_14]: The very richest in our society have got richer.

676
00:58:49,032 --> 00:58:54,223
[SPEAKER_14]: There's been more and more tax giveaways at the top end and more and more charges at the other end.

677
00:58:54,523 --> 00:58:56,187
[SPEAKER_14]: It's time to rebalance it.

678
00:58:56,447 --> 00:59:08,492
[SPEAKER_14]: Our manifesto is a serious, well thought out document that I believe is getting a lot of support and people are very excited by the idea of how we could do things differently.

679
00:59:13,872 --> 00:59:21,541
[SPEAKER_28]: You say this manifesto is serious and well thought out and you speak about creating an equal society free from racism and anti-Semitism.

680
00:59:22,062 --> 00:59:29,590
[SPEAKER_28]: But how can I believe a word of this when you as party leader have failed to expel one of your own members, Ken Livingstone, for his anti-Semitic remarks?

681
00:59:35,057 --> 00:59:40,403
[SPEAKER_14]: There is no place for anti-Semitism anywhere in our society and certainly not in our party.

682
00:59:40,501 --> 00:59:49,113
[SPEAKER_14]: Members have been suspended if they've committed any remarks that can be seen to be of an anti-Semitic nature.

683
00:59:49,554 --> 00:59:52,398
[SPEAKER_14]: Those that have done that are suspended.

684
00:59:52,578 --> 00:59:59,869
[SPEAKER_14]: We have a process that is independent of me within the party, which investigates these and makes a decision on it.

685
01:00:00,610 --> 01:00:04,956
[SPEAKER_14]: I deplore racism in any form whatsoever.

686
01:00:05,054 --> 01:00:14,305
[SPEAKER_14]: The way in which the Jewish people have suffered down the centuries, the Holocaust and all that went with it, was the most appalling stain in the history of mankind.

687
01:00:15,146 --> 01:00:20,412
[SPEAKER_14]: And I believe we have to fight racism in any form, with every fibre of our being.

688
01:00:20,652 --> 01:00:25,598
[SPEAKER_14]: A society that cannot challenge racism is a society that is heading for division.

689
01:00:25,938 --> 01:00:30,083
[SPEAKER_14]: I will not tolerate it in our party or anywhere else.

690
01:00:32,307 --> 01:00:38,435
[SPEAKER_28]: If it's something that's so important to you, how will you suffice with only suspending him for a short period of time?

691
01:00:38,455 --> 01:00:39,997
[SPEAKER_28]: How is it not enough to expel him permanently?

692
01:00:40,017 --> 01:00:47,186
[SPEAKER_14]: He has been suspended and further investigations may or may not happen after the election, but he is suspended from membership.

693
01:00:47,426 --> 01:00:51,251
[SPEAKER_14]: But he's suspended so that the investigation can take place.

694
01:00:51,271 --> 01:00:52,993
[SPEAKER_16]: All right, the woman there on the gangway, you.

695
01:00:54,054 --> 01:00:56,217
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, you.

696
01:00:56,237 --> 01:00:59,361
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, I heard you recently commented that

697
01:00:59,678 --> 01:01:07,991
[SPEAKER_03]: black and ethnic minorities potential has been locked under Conservatives and you plan to free up and unlock it.

698
01:01:08,092 --> 01:01:10,956
[SPEAKER_03]: I just want some clarification as to how exactly you plan to do it.

699
01:01:11,697 --> 01:01:13,801
[SPEAKER_03]: Sorry, I didn't fully hear the question.

700
01:01:13,861 --> 01:01:15,503
[SPEAKER_03]: There was a camera right in front of you at the time.

701
01:01:15,924 --> 01:01:16,485
[SPEAKER_14]: Sorry about that.

702
01:01:16,625 --> 01:01:21,433
[SPEAKER_03]: I said there was a recent comment that I read in the news about you purporting that

703
01:01:21,717 --> 01:01:25,309
[SPEAKER_03]: black and ethnic minorities potential has been locked under conservatives.

704
01:01:26,152 --> 01:01:31,812
[SPEAKER_03]: So I just want some clarification as to how you'd free up or unlock it or help.

705
01:01:32,264 --> 01:01:33,306
[SPEAKER_03]: in that regard?

706
01:01:33,506 --> 01:01:36,511
[SPEAKER_14]: The issues are of poverty in Britain.

707
01:01:36,751 --> 01:01:42,821
[SPEAKER_14]: The issues are of differential levels of spending in inner city areas compared to other areas.

708
01:01:43,142 --> 01:01:58,947
[SPEAKER_14]: And there are serious issues about the number of young black people, particularly young men, who are part of the criminal justice system, end up in youth custody or youth justice institutions, or those that end up in mental health institutions.

709
01:01:58,927 --> 01:02:04,238
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we have to look very seriously at levels of racism within our society.

710
01:02:04,599 --> 01:02:10,891
[SPEAKER_14]: If you like racism that's almost of an institutionalized nature, that has to be looked at.

711
01:02:11,212 --> 01:02:14,218
[SPEAKER_14]: And one of the issues we put forward was consider

712
01:02:14,198 --> 01:02:23,131
[SPEAKER_14]: how difficult it can be for somebody with an African name or a Muslim name to get a shortlist or get an interview for a job compared to others.

713
01:02:23,191 --> 01:02:38,232
[SPEAKER_14]: And so one suggestion, it's a suggestion, it may become a policy, is that we should have blind applications for jobs where there's no name involved, there's merely a description of your skills and your ability and your qualifications, so that there can be a fair assessment of that person.

714
01:02:38,593 --> 01:02:41,016
[SPEAKER_14]: Because we are,

715
01:02:41,350 --> 01:02:45,054
[SPEAKER_14]: a multi-ethnic, multi-lingual, multi-cultural society.

716
01:02:45,635 --> 01:02:55,106
[SPEAKER_14]: If it doesn't treat everybody equally and give everybody a decent chance, then we end up with poverty, we end up with discrimination and we end up with divisions.

717
01:02:55,507 --> 01:03:02,515
[SPEAKER_14]: I want to see a country that comes together and is not divided and apart by poverty or by discrimination.

718
01:03:05,819 --> 01:03:13,559
[SPEAKER_16]: We may come back to education and the economy in a moment, but let's have this question from Adam Murgatroyd, please.

719
01:03:13,940 --> 01:03:14,722
[SPEAKER_16]: Adam Murgatroyd.

720
01:03:15,604 --> 01:03:19,474
[SPEAKER_41]: If Britain were under imminent threat from nuclear weapons, how would you react?

721
01:03:21,192 --> 01:03:39,201
[SPEAKER_14]: I would do everything I can to ensure that any threat is actually dealt with earlier on by negotiations and by talks, so that we do adhere to our obligations under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, that we do encourage China

722
01:03:39,181 --> 01:03:44,710
[SPEAKER_14]: in its work in trying to bring about six-party talks in resolving the issue in North Korea.

723
01:03:44,971 --> 01:03:54,186
[SPEAKER_14]: And we do follow the lead that President Obama took in doing a deal with Iran which would result in them not developing the nuclear capability.

724
01:03:54,335 --> 01:04:01,148
[SPEAKER_14]: I think the idea of anyone ever using a nuclear weapon anywhere in the world is utterly appalling and terrible.

725
01:04:01,228 --> 01:04:07,920
[SPEAKER_14]: It would result in the destruction of the lives and communities and environment for millions of people.

726
01:04:08,160 --> 01:04:12,569
[SPEAKER_14]: And so I would be actively engaged to ensure that danger didn't come about.

727
01:04:12,809 --> 01:04:16,596
[SPEAKER_14]: I would also be very aware of other dangers that we face.

728
01:04:16,576 --> 01:04:20,163
[SPEAKER_14]: Cyber attacks hit our National Health Service a couple of weeks ago.

729
01:04:20,744 --> 01:04:27,937
[SPEAKER_14]: The dreadful terrorist attack in Manchester indicates the danger of individual acts of terrorism that can take lives.

730
01:04:28,257 --> 01:04:30,902
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to be secure here.

731
01:04:30,942 --> 01:04:34,008
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to protect our society and our country.

732
01:04:34,248 --> 01:04:39,057
[SPEAKER_14]: But we also have to engage in the rest of the world to make sure we don't have huge

733
01:04:39,037 --> 01:04:47,037
[SPEAKER_14]: ungoverned spaces such as in Libya, which can become the basis of some terrible events that are going to take the lives of many other people.

734
01:04:47,237 --> 01:04:50,425
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to deal with those issues here and globally.

735
01:04:50,566 --> 01:04:53,974
[SPEAKER_14]: That is the function of a responsible government.

736
01:04:56,975 --> 01:04:59,739
[SPEAKER_16]: Your party is committed to renewing Trident.

737
01:04:59,779 --> 01:05:02,743
[SPEAKER_16]: Are you saying there are no circumstances in which you'd use a nuclear weapon?

738
01:05:02,943 --> 01:05:05,747
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm saying that our party has committed to renewing Trident.

739
01:05:05,767 --> 01:05:09,692
[SPEAKER_14]: That was a decision taken by a party conference and indeed taken by Parliament.

740
01:05:09,832 --> 01:05:17,582
[SPEAKER_14]: I would view the idea of having to use a nuclear weapon as something that was resulting in a failure in the whole world's diplomatic

741
01:05:17,562 --> 01:05:18,123
[SPEAKER_14]: system.

742
01:05:18,164 --> 01:05:20,530
[SPEAKER_14]: There has to be no first use.

743
01:05:20,590 --> 01:05:25,863
[SPEAKER_14]: There has to be a process of engagement to bring about, ultimately, global nuclear disarmament.

744
01:05:25,883 --> 01:05:27,207
[SPEAKER_14]: It's not going to happen quickly.

745
01:05:27,467 --> 01:05:28,530
[SPEAKER_14]: It's not going to happen easily.

746
01:05:28,590 --> 01:05:31,217
[SPEAKER_14]: But we have to have that wish.

747
01:05:32,159 --> 01:05:35,866
[SPEAKER_14]: countenance a world in which we could all be destroyed by nuclear war.

748
01:05:35,886 --> 01:05:41,617
[SPEAKER_16]: You say no first use and you wouldn't use, you wouldn't push the button in first use.

749
01:05:41,637 --> 01:05:45,645
[SPEAKER_16]: In retaliatory use would you use nuclear weapons that your party is reviving?

750
01:05:45,665 --> 01:05:52,598
[SPEAKER_14]: The weapon is there and I would say no first use of the weapon and I think that has to be the basis on what we do.

751
01:05:52,578 --> 01:05:54,000
[SPEAKER_14]: Adam, does that answer your question?

752
01:05:54,020 --> 01:05:54,941
[SPEAKER_16]: Do you want to come back on it?

753
01:05:54,981 --> 01:05:58,585
[SPEAKER_41]: I find it incredibly concerning that you wouldn't ever commit to doing that.

754
01:05:58,605 --> 01:06:01,308
[SPEAKER_41]: It's our safety that we need to look out first and foremost any government.

755
01:06:01,708 --> 01:06:07,034
[SPEAKER_41]: But what particularly annoys me is that Trident isn't just for, heaven forbid, a potential Corbyn government.

756
01:06:07,074 --> 01:06:08,135
[SPEAKER_41]: It goes long beyond that.

757
01:06:09,076 --> 01:06:11,519
[SPEAKER_41]: You know, many, many decades into the future.

758
01:06:12,120 --> 01:06:16,825
[SPEAKER_41]: So when you're making the decision whether to support this or not, it's not just for right here, right now.

759
01:06:16,865 --> 01:06:19,648
[SPEAKER_41]: It's threats that we can face in the future.

760
01:06:24,860 --> 01:06:25,441
[SPEAKER_14]: Fair point.

761
01:06:26,061 --> 01:06:43,421
[SPEAKER_14]: But we have to do everything we can, obviously to protect ourselves, but the best protection is having good and reasonable relationships with the rest of the world so we don't descend into a mentality where there are military blocks starting threatening each other.

762
01:06:43,662 --> 01:06:48,507
[SPEAKER_14]: And I'm utterly determined to do everything I can to bring about a more peaceful world.

763
01:06:48,527 --> 01:06:54,394
[SPEAKER_14]: I've spent a lot of my life with UN and other organisations trying to bring about

764
01:06:54,796 --> 01:07:00,267
[SPEAKER_14]: principle of no first use, principles of disarmament and principles of bringing about

765
01:07:01,040 --> 01:07:02,122
[SPEAKER_14]: peace around the world.

766
01:07:02,162 --> 01:07:04,565
[SPEAKER_14]: That surely is something we can all work for.

767
01:07:04,906 --> 01:07:15,601
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we have to recognize that there is deep inequality and injustice in the world, but the threats are, as I said, cyber security and terrorism.

768
01:07:15,662 --> 01:07:29,562
[SPEAKER_14]: The other threats are actually of environmental disaster around the world and large numbers of people fleeing from environmental disaster, in effect, environmental refugees, which is why I was so disappointed in President Trump's decision

769
01:07:29,542 --> 01:07:35,351
[SPEAKER_14]: particularly in view of what has been achieved by people working together to try and protect and sustain this planet.

770
01:07:35,651 --> 01:07:36,713
[SPEAKER_14]: We've only got one planet.

771
01:07:37,754 --> 01:07:40,859
[SPEAKER_14]: Let's get together when we live on it and, above all, let's not destroy it.

772
01:07:41,079 --> 01:07:49,812
[SPEAKER_16]: Can we just come back to the nuclear issue?

773
01:07:49,852 --> 01:07:51,735
[SPEAKER_16]: You are Prime Minister.

774
01:07:52,137 --> 01:07:54,219
[SPEAKER_16]: You've said you would have no first use.

775
01:07:54,259 --> 01:08:00,786
[SPEAKER_16]: You wouldn't countenance Britain's nuclear deterrent, which your party is restoring, rebuilding, maintaining.

776
01:08:01,126 --> 01:08:02,748
[SPEAKER_16]: You wouldn't have a first use.

777
01:08:02,768 --> 01:08:07,393
[SPEAKER_16]: And it raises the question, he said under direct attack, would you use it in retaliation?

778
01:08:07,633 --> 01:08:15,541
[SPEAKER_16]: As Prime Minister, you're speaking to the country about what you would do with the most expensive defence weapon that we have.

779
01:08:16,002 --> 01:08:18,164
[SPEAKER_16]: Are you saying you would never use it under any circumstance?

780
01:08:18,184 --> 01:08:21,908
[SPEAKER_14]: People tell me the most effective use of it is not to use it because it's there.

781
01:08:22,850 --> 01:08:25,032
[SPEAKER_16]: Sorry, you're dodging the question, aren't you?

782
01:08:25,092 --> 01:08:29,257
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm saying, are you saying there are no circumstances under which you'd use it?

783
01:08:29,397 --> 01:08:34,583
[SPEAKER_14]: Any circumstances where anyone's prepared to use a nuclear weapon is disastrous for the whole planet.

784
01:08:34,603 --> 01:08:44,394
[SPEAKER_14]: That is why there has to be a policy of disarmament globally, but through a multilateral policy, not a unilateral policy.

785
01:08:44,414 --> 01:08:49,920
[SPEAKER_16]: But that's the ideal, but what about the reality where you're faced with a prospect that you may have to use it?

786
01:08:52,651 --> 01:08:55,436
[SPEAKER_14]: I just asked you for a simple answer.

787
01:08:55,677 --> 01:09:00,947
[SPEAKER_14]: The reality is that we have to obviously try to protect ourselves.

788
01:09:01,448 --> 01:09:03,773
[SPEAKER_14]: We would not use it as first use.

789
01:09:03,793 --> 01:09:06,738
[SPEAKER_14]: And if we did use it, millions are going to die.

790
01:09:07,019 --> 01:09:08,702
[SPEAKER_14]: You have to think this thing through.

791
01:09:11,737 --> 01:09:13,860
[SPEAKER_19]: I'll decide on the circumstances at the time.

792
01:09:16,484 --> 01:09:18,246
[SPEAKER_19]: Would you use it as second use?

793
01:09:18,687 --> 01:09:25,457
[SPEAKER_19]: Or would you allow North Korea or some idiot in Iran to bomb us and then say, oh, we'd better start talking?

794
01:09:25,677 --> 01:09:26,779
[SPEAKER_19]: You'd be too late.

795
01:09:26,799 --> 01:09:30,564
[SPEAKER_14]: No, of course not.

796
01:09:30,584 --> 01:09:31,425
[SPEAKER_14]: You're going to have to do it first place.

797
01:09:31,445 --> 01:09:31,806
[SPEAKER_14]: No, of course not.

798
01:09:31,826 --> 01:09:32,547
[SPEAKER_14]: Of course I would not do that.

799
01:09:34,062 --> 01:09:35,444
[SPEAKER_19]: You would allow them to do it?

800
01:09:36,164 --> 01:09:45,455
[SPEAKER_14]: Of course not, because that is why I made the point a short time ago about the need for President Obama's agreement with Iran to be upheld.

801
01:09:46,156 --> 01:09:50,822
[SPEAKER_14]: It's quite important, actually, and also to promote disarmament in Korea.

802
01:09:51,022 --> 01:09:53,685
[SPEAKER_14]: That is difficult, I appreciate, but...

803
01:09:53,705 --> 01:09:54,226
[SPEAKER_14]: Impossible.

804
01:09:54,646 --> 01:09:56,028
[SPEAKER_21]: Well...

805
01:09:56,048 --> 01:09:56,548
[SPEAKER_21]: Impossible.

806
01:09:57,189 --> 01:09:58,591
[SPEAKER_43]: Ask the Chinese what they're trying to do.

807
01:09:58,891 --> 01:09:59,732
[SPEAKER_21]: You up there.

808
01:09:59,915 --> 01:10:03,460
[SPEAKER_43]: Yeah, you're asking a massive wish when you've got one of the biggest arsenals by your side.

809
01:10:04,963 --> 01:10:08,628
[SPEAKER_43]: I'd rather have it and not use it than not have it at all, especially in today's day and age.

810
01:10:14,717 --> 01:10:18,563
[SPEAKER_16]: Do you want to comment on that?

811
01:10:18,583 --> 01:10:18,824
[SPEAKER_16]: All right.

812
01:10:19,164 --> 01:10:19,905
[SPEAKER_16]: Anybody?

813
01:10:20,086 --> 01:10:20,907
[SPEAKER_16]: The woman there.

814
01:10:21,047 --> 01:10:21,267
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes.

815
01:10:21,327 --> 01:10:22,589
[SPEAKER_16]: Let's just stick with this and then we'll move on.

816
01:10:22,629 --> 01:10:23,070
[SPEAKER_34]: Yes.

817
01:10:23,287 --> 01:10:25,073
[SPEAKER_34]: I actually have a question regarding human rights.

818
01:10:25,434 --> 01:10:26,778
[SPEAKER_16]: All right, use your question.

819
01:10:27,019 --> 01:10:33,178
[SPEAKER_34]: Just before, I don't understand why everyone in this room seems so keen on killing millions of people with a nuclear weapon.

820
01:10:44,313 --> 01:10:49,647
[SPEAKER_34]: I think it's worth moving on from that particular debate because we are talking about murdering people.

821
01:10:50,509 --> 01:10:53,457
[SPEAKER_34]: I want to ask a specific question about your immigration policy.

822
01:10:53,919 --> 01:11:00,516
[SPEAKER_34]: You've mentioned that you want to reunite families specifically that have been forced apart by Theresa May's current migration policies.

823
01:11:00,496 --> 01:11:03,542
[SPEAKER_34]: Myself, my husband's recording this in America as he's at work.

824
01:11:03,582 --> 01:11:05,004
[SPEAKER_34]: He was deported in December.

825
01:11:05,104 --> 01:11:12,799
[SPEAKER_34]: He was told he was too highly educated despite studying here, getting an undergraduate and a master's degree, invested a lot in this country.

826
01:11:13,360 --> 01:11:21,795
[SPEAKER_34]: I want to know whether you would consider reducing the financial threshold for family migration to be further in line with the national minimum wage or living wage.

827
01:11:22,248 --> 01:11:24,613
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes, our manifesto has addressed this issue.

828
01:11:25,074 --> 01:11:31,226
[SPEAKER_14]: It is very painful some of the decisions that are made where the frankly arbitrary level of income is chosen.

829
01:11:31,627 --> 01:11:43,311
[SPEAKER_14]: Couples are split apart, families are split apart, and people like the person you're talking about have invested a huge amount of time and energy into this country are then removed from this country.

830
01:11:43,291 --> 01:11:43,852
[SPEAKER_14]: Who loses?

831
01:11:44,193 --> 01:11:44,754
[SPEAKER_14]: We all lose.

832
01:11:45,095 --> 01:11:48,541
[SPEAKER_14]: The family loses, the children lose, we lose as a society.

833
01:11:48,922 --> 01:11:54,413
[SPEAKER_14]: And we will change those immigration laws so that there can be proper family reunion.

834
01:11:54,453 --> 01:11:56,878
[SPEAKER_14]: I think that has to be the right and sensible thing to do.

835
01:11:57,095 --> 01:12:03,066
[SPEAKER_16]: Are you in favour of reducing immigration overall into this country?

836
01:12:03,847 --> 01:12:15,829
[SPEAKER_14]: What I think will happen is this, that we have managed migration from outside Europe which is based on family reunion and skill needs or investment.

837
01:12:15,809 --> 01:12:19,053
[SPEAKER_14]: We have at the moment free movement from within the European Union.

838
01:12:19,073 --> 01:12:20,735
[SPEAKER_14]: That ends when we leave the European Union.

839
01:12:21,015 --> 01:12:24,179
[SPEAKER_14]: So we'll then have to be managed migration from Europe.

840
01:12:24,199 --> 01:12:29,586
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to also recognize that those who have migrated to this country have made a massive contribution to our society.

841
01:12:29,946 --> 01:12:34,832
[SPEAKER_14]: The health of all of us has depended, depends on the work that's done by many people that made their homes here.

842
01:12:35,373 --> 01:12:43,943
[SPEAKER_14]: What I think will happen is there will probably be some reduction in European migration because we will also prevent there being

843
01:12:43,923 --> 01:12:59,893
[SPEAKER_14]: recruitment of groups of low-paid workers from Central Europe to come here to undermine existing conditions that are often not very good themselves and damage the life chance of people in this country and be not actually very good for those that have been brought in.

844
01:12:59,953 --> 01:13:07,247
[SPEAKER_14]: So we will end overseas-only recruitment and end those contractual arrangements by which people are brought in, particularly into the construction industry.

845
01:13:07,227 --> 01:13:25,187
[SPEAKER_14]: But we also, if I may say so, just have another issue which we do have to address, and that is the skill shortage and skill problem in Britain, because we have not invested enough in industrial training, we've not invested enough in skill training, we've not invested enough in training more doctors or more nurses in this country.

846
01:13:25,487 --> 01:13:28,010
[SPEAKER_14]: Until we do that, then we've got a big problem.

847
01:13:28,070 --> 01:13:33,977
[SPEAKER_14]: And so our whole approach to our manifesto is about investment for the future.

848
01:13:37,332 --> 01:13:46,094
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm thinking of what your shadow Brexit Secretary, Keir Starmer, said, which is there's been a huge amount of immigration over the last ten years.

849
01:13:46,114 --> 01:13:47,658
[SPEAKER_16]: People are concerned about it.

850
01:13:47,678 --> 01:13:48,621
[SPEAKER_16]: I think it should be reduced.

851
01:13:48,982 --> 01:13:53,012
[SPEAKER_16]: When people voted Brexit, do you think immigration was at the forefront?

852
01:13:52,992 --> 01:13:53,693
[SPEAKER_16]: of their minds?

853
01:13:53,713 --> 01:13:55,115
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it was a big factor in it.

854
01:13:55,175 --> 01:13:57,959
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't think it was the only factor, but it was a big factor.

855
01:13:58,259 --> 01:14:11,338
[SPEAKER_14]: There is also an issue that communities and local government are often not sufficiently funded to deal with groups of people coming in, and so we would restore what Gordon Brown had in 2009, which was a migrant impact fund.

856
01:14:11,538 --> 01:14:14,003
[SPEAKER_16]: One or two more people, I'll come to you and then we'll go on to another question.

857
01:14:14,023 --> 01:14:14,825
[SPEAKER_16]: Can we get a microphone to you?

858
01:14:14,845 --> 01:14:16,608
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, go on, far away.

859
01:14:16,628 --> 01:14:24,704
[SPEAKER_05]: Mr Corbyn, we've talked about nuclear weapons before, but one thing that worries me more at the moment, as somebody who's grown up in a family business, is the changes in the minimum wage.

860
01:14:24,905 --> 01:14:27,049
[SPEAKER_05]: I read your manifesto yesterday.

861
01:14:27,029 --> 01:14:30,272
[SPEAKER_05]: and you are planning on increasing the minimum wage to £10.

862
01:14:30,332 --> 01:14:37,619
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, the current plan for the national living wage forecasts say that up to 60,000 people could lose their jobs because of those increases in wages.

863
01:14:38,059 --> 01:14:47,868
[SPEAKER_05]: So, firstly, how many jobs... What statistic have you been given by your economists or whoever works for you as to how many jobs will be lost if it goes up to £10 an hour?

864
01:14:48,248 --> 01:14:57,036
[SPEAKER_05]: And secondly, how will you help the 3 million micro-businesses in the United Kingdom who employ many people on the minimum wage and already struggle to do that?

865
01:14:57,016 --> 01:15:01,185
[SPEAKER_05]: Fair point and fair question.

866
01:15:01,205 --> 01:15:16,459
[SPEAKER_14]: When the minimum wage was first introduced by the Labour government after the 1997 election there were a lot of similar concerns and predictions which turned out not to be the case and in fact there was not any substantial number of jobless.

867
01:15:16,439 --> 01:15:19,103
[SPEAKER_05]: is because the wage increases were so small.

868
01:15:19,123 --> 01:15:25,793
[SPEAKER_05]: If you look at the economic comments around that time, the wage increases were so small, all the commentators said that.

869
01:15:26,153 --> 01:15:27,656
[SPEAKER_05]: This is a massive wage change.

870
01:15:27,696 --> 01:15:34,566
[SPEAKER_05]: There is such a bigger margin of error now in your policies than what was brought in in 1999.

871
01:15:35,693 --> 01:15:37,536
[SPEAKER_14]: Can I come back to your point?

872
01:15:37,976 --> 01:15:40,720
[SPEAKER_14]: What we're proposing is £10 an hour by 2020.

873
01:15:41,701 --> 01:15:43,043
[SPEAKER_14]: That would be a living wage.

874
01:15:43,143 --> 01:15:51,295
[SPEAKER_14]: That would reduce our Department of Work and Pensions bill somewhat because you'd be reducing in-work benefit payments because people are being paid more.

875
01:15:51,996 --> 01:15:56,622
[SPEAKER_14]: There are many big companies that could well afford to pay it and shouldn't be just paying the minimum wage.

876
01:15:57,209 --> 01:16:01,535
[SPEAKER_14]: There are companies like, I suspect, yours, small companies that would have problems.

877
01:16:01,815 --> 01:16:03,037
[SPEAKER_14]: We fully recognize that.

878
01:16:03,337 --> 01:16:14,072
[SPEAKER_14]: We would therefore work with them, either to give them tax relief or support, in order to make sure the living wage, the real living wage, was paid, but they didn't close down as a result of it.

879
01:16:14,112 --> 01:16:17,977
[SPEAKER_14]: Because as a society, we have six million people earning less than the living wage.

880
01:16:17,997 --> 01:16:20,460
[SPEAKER_14]: We have a million people on zero-hours contracts.

881
01:16:20,721 --> 01:16:25,868
[SPEAKER_14]: We have wage levels, the proportion of national income actually falling at the present time.

882
01:16:26,168 --> 01:16:26,929
[SPEAKER_14]: I think

883
01:16:26,909 --> 01:16:32,156
[SPEAKER_14]: more money in the pockets will mean people are better off, but it will also be an economic boost itself.

884
01:16:32,316 --> 01:16:36,101
[SPEAKER_14]: I absolutely recognise the problems for small and micro businesses.

885
01:16:36,181 --> 01:16:40,567
[SPEAKER_14]: That's why there would be a pathway to it for them with support from the government to achieve it.

886
01:16:45,033 --> 01:16:48,478
[SPEAKER_16]: I just want to hear from Edward Robbins because Mr Corbyn just mentioned the issue.

887
01:16:48,498 --> 01:16:49,339
[SPEAKER_16]: Edward Robbins.

888
01:16:51,310 --> 01:16:52,432
[SPEAKER_16]: Where is Edward Robbins?

889
01:16:52,973 --> 01:16:53,474
[SPEAKER_16]: Put your hand up.

890
01:16:53,494 --> 01:16:53,875
[SPEAKER_16]: Where are you?

891
01:16:53,895 --> 01:16:54,155
[SPEAKER_16]: There.

892
01:16:54,215 --> 01:16:55,217
[SPEAKER_16]: Yes, good.

893
01:16:55,257 --> 01:16:55,517
[SPEAKER_25]: Yeah.

894
01:16:55,578 --> 01:17:00,707
[SPEAKER_25]: Zero-hours contracts provide an easy way for students like myself to get casual, flexible work.

895
01:17:01,207 --> 01:17:03,952
[SPEAKER_25]: How will scrapping these contracts affect us?

896
01:17:03,972 --> 01:17:08,340
[SPEAKER_14]: Labour policy to scrap zero-hours contracts.

897
01:17:08,557 --> 01:17:15,988
[SPEAKER_14]: First of all, zero-hours contracts for many people mean a lifetime of stress and a lifetime of great difficulty.

898
01:17:16,168 --> 01:17:20,395
[SPEAKER_14]: Imagine what it's like if your sole source of income is a zero-hours contract job.

899
01:17:20,415 --> 01:17:26,143
[SPEAKER_14]: You wake up in the morning, you look at your mobile phone and see if your employer wants you that day or not, that week or not.

900
01:17:26,123 --> 01:17:41,685
[SPEAKER_14]: you don't know what your income is going to be.

901
01:17:41,665 --> 01:17:49,154
[SPEAKER_14]: pay you X number of hours per week on a flexible basis so that you will have an average pay of, say, 10 hours per week.

902
01:17:49,434 --> 01:17:59,927
[SPEAKER_14]: That means those people are loyal to the company, those people know what their income is going to be, and that seems to me a much fairer way of doing it, so you then have some security of what's going on.

903
01:18:00,087 --> 01:18:05,394
[SPEAKER_14]: And there are some employers that do that in towns with a large student population, with students, and it works quite well.

904
01:18:05,975 --> 01:18:06,695
[SPEAKER_14]: What's your reaction?

905
01:18:07,957 --> 01:18:11,301
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm not going to stop you working, it's okay.

906
01:18:12,462 --> 01:18:26,183
[SPEAKER_25]: Well, yeah, I was talking about more coming from us having the option for students and us to go to employers and say, we want to work this time and this time, and not just getting told you're working this many hours this week.

907
01:18:26,204 --> 01:18:27,546
[SPEAKER_16]: Working when you choose, really.

908
01:18:27,986 --> 01:18:32,293
[SPEAKER_25]: Yeah, the so-called gig economy, like riding for delivery services.

909
01:18:32,273 --> 01:18:37,621
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes, I think the agreement should be that you come to a discussion with the employer.

910
01:18:38,081 --> 01:18:45,132
[SPEAKER_14]: I can work for three hours on a Monday, six hours on a Thursday, two hours at a weekend, something like that.

911
01:18:45,392 --> 01:18:46,874
[SPEAKER_14]: And that's my work pattern.

912
01:18:46,894 --> 01:18:49,218
[SPEAKER_14]: It's not simple to manage for any employer.

913
01:18:49,458 --> 01:18:50,319
[SPEAKER_14]: I fully understand that.

914
01:18:50,339 --> 01:18:53,083
[SPEAKER_14]: But it does give the security to the individual.

915
01:18:53,343 --> 01:18:59,993
[SPEAKER_14]: It also gives the employer a wide range of workers that are working and will be loyal to that employer.

916
01:19:00,193 --> 01:19:01,335
[SPEAKER_14]: All right, you sir at the back there.

917
01:19:01,957 --> 01:19:04,913
[SPEAKER_20]: Why have you never regarded the IRA as terrorists?

918
01:19:11,525 --> 01:19:29,682
[SPEAKER_14]: I have deplored all acts of terrorism by anybody in Northern Ireland or anywhere else and I think the Good Friday Agreement was a huge achievement that was brought about when both communities recognised their shared but different past and brought about the idea of a power-sharing government in Northern Ireland.

919
01:19:29,762 --> 01:19:32,908
[SPEAKER_14]: I think that was an enormous achievement and

920
01:19:32,888 --> 01:19:35,714
[SPEAKER_14]: It's been copied elsewhere in the world as a way forward.

921
01:19:36,034 --> 01:19:40,523
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't approve of any terrorism of any sort or any terrorist acts of any sort.

922
01:19:40,543 --> 01:19:43,369
[SPEAKER_14]: It only divides communities and kills people.

923
01:19:43,429 --> 01:19:48,079
[SPEAKER_14]: They killed a lot of people.

924
01:19:48,099 --> 01:19:49,602
[SPEAKER_14]: Does that answer the question for you?

925
01:19:49,622 --> 01:19:51,285
[SPEAKER_20]: They did kill a lot of people, didn't they?

926
01:19:52,953 --> 01:19:54,155
[SPEAKER_14]: All deaths are wrong.

927
01:19:54,355 --> 01:19:55,477
[SPEAKER_14]: All killing is wrong.

928
01:19:55,617 --> 01:20:01,085
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to develop, and we did in Northern Ireland eventually, a very effective peace process.

929
01:20:01,105 --> 01:20:08,997
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think we should pay tribute to those in the unionist community, as well as those in the nationalist community, for coming together to bring about that peace process.

930
01:20:09,137 --> 01:20:11,701
[SPEAKER_14]: It was a truly remarkable experience.

931
01:20:11,741 --> 01:20:12,422
[SPEAKER_14]: OK. You, sir?

932
01:20:14,264 --> 01:20:14,465
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes.

933
01:20:15,306 --> 01:20:16,027
[SPEAKER_14]: Oh, you didn't want to speak.

934
01:20:16,387 --> 01:20:16,568
[SPEAKER_14]: Me?

935
01:20:16,748 --> 01:20:18,150
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, I thought you had your hand up.

936
01:20:18,687 --> 01:20:19,850
[SPEAKER_15]: You've got the microphone over your head.

937
01:20:19,870 --> 01:20:20,412
[SPEAKER_15]: You're all right.

938
01:20:21,154 --> 01:20:23,279
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, you said you didn't support the IRA.

939
01:20:23,339 --> 01:20:28,674
[SPEAKER_15]: You've also supported Hamas and other terrorist organizations.

940
01:20:28,974 --> 01:20:33,968
[SPEAKER_15]: How do you expect the British people to vote for you to go into number 10 when you sat there and supported them?

941
01:20:34,289 --> 01:20:35,211
[SPEAKER_15]: We've seen you.

942
01:20:37,756 --> 01:20:41,120
[SPEAKER_14]: I have not supported any of those organisations.

943
01:20:41,140 --> 01:20:57,117
[SPEAKER_14]: What I've said is, and I'm sure you'd probably agree with it, that if you're to bring about a peace process anywhere, be it in the Middle East, be it in Ireland, be it in a different situation in, say, Colombia or anywhere else, there has to be a coming together at some point.

944
01:20:57,137 --> 01:21:00,600
[SPEAKER_15]: You were talking to them when they were killing their people, their women and children.

945
01:21:00,620 --> 01:21:01,601
[SPEAKER_15]: You were talking to them.

946
01:21:01,741 --> 01:21:03,223
[SPEAKER_15]: There has to be.

947
01:21:04,182 --> 01:21:08,789
[SPEAKER_14]: I was talking to representatives of the Republican movement.

948
01:21:08,969 --> 01:21:09,229
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes.

949
01:21:09,770 --> 01:21:12,293
[SPEAKER_14]: Actually, so was the government at the same time.

950
01:21:12,854 --> 01:21:19,524
[SPEAKER_14]: Ian Paisley was indeed thrown out of Parliament when he told the government, told Margaret Thatcher, she was actually talking to them.

951
01:21:19,544 --> 01:21:19,984
[SPEAKER_14]: Do you know what?

952
01:21:20,285 --> 01:21:25,312
[SPEAKER_14]: I voted that Ian Paisley shouldn't be thrown out of Parliament because I thought his voice should be heard in Parliament.

953
01:21:25,672 --> 01:21:29,938
[SPEAKER_14]: You have to bring about a peace process by talking to people that you don't agree with.

954
01:21:30,099 --> 01:21:33,143
[SPEAKER_14]: If you just talk amongst your friends, you're not going to get a peace process.

955
01:21:34,490 --> 01:21:41,608
[SPEAKER_16]: Are you done you keep poking the man in front of you do you want him to speak me again?

956
01:21:41,949 --> 01:21:45,377
[SPEAKER_16]: Do you want to speak

957
01:21:46,184 --> 01:21:47,185
[SPEAKER_16]: Are you trying to speak on that?

958
01:21:47,226 --> 01:21:50,871
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm not, but I can do it.

959
01:21:50,891 --> 01:21:52,894
[SPEAKER_21]: OK, well... Yeah, you've talked to these people in the past.

960
01:21:52,914 --> 01:21:55,177
[SPEAKER_21]: You talked earlier on when talking about the nuclear option.

961
01:21:55,818 --> 01:21:57,621
[SPEAKER_21]: Talking is the way you want to go.

962
01:21:57,681 --> 01:22:02,388
[SPEAKER_21]: David often says at the end of programmes, telling the public to press the red button.

963
01:22:02,408 --> 01:22:07,315
[SPEAKER_21]: Are you saying you will never, ever, under any circumstances, press a red button?

964
01:22:08,594 --> 01:22:13,144
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we've discussed this at some length about the aspirations we all have.

965
01:22:13,745 --> 01:22:17,313
[SPEAKER_14]: I do not want to be responsible for the destruction of millions of people, neither do you.

966
01:22:17,693 --> 01:22:26,873
[SPEAKER_14]: Therefore we have to work for a world where they're not available and not used.

967
01:22:27,680 --> 01:22:37,805
[SPEAKER_40]: Just to bring it back to economics, it's all very well for a socialist to stand there with his very nice little red book and say, we're going to fund all these lovely programs by taking more money from big business.

968
01:22:37,905 --> 01:22:45,283
[SPEAKER_40]: But what's your plan for the economy when those businesses turn around and say, OK, you can keep your high taxes, we'll go elsewhere?

969
01:22:50,123 --> 01:22:54,456
[SPEAKER_14]: You look at the businesses we're talking about are actually doing very well.

970
01:22:54,516 --> 01:23:00,353
[SPEAKER_14]: They've done extremely well over the past six years because their tax have been cut a great deal.

971
01:23:00,400 --> 01:23:04,886
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we have to look at the problems of our public services.

972
01:23:05,186 --> 01:23:10,032
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to look at the issues of what kind of economic future we have.

973
01:23:10,253 --> 01:23:19,564
[SPEAKER_14]: We cannot go on being a low-waged economy, underspending on our public services, investing less than any other industrialised country in our future.

974
01:23:20,105 --> 01:23:26,273
[SPEAKER_14]: I would much prefer that we develop a national investment bank and strategy regionally based

975
01:23:26,253 --> 01:23:33,646
[SPEAKER_14]: to improve rail, broadband, road communications, that we improve investment in our industry for the future.

976
01:23:33,967 --> 01:23:37,834
[SPEAKER_14]: We have a lower proportion of manufacturing industry than Germany.

977
01:23:38,154 --> 01:23:40,218
[SPEAKER_14]: We have a lower level of productivity than Germany.

978
01:23:40,418 --> 01:23:42,642
[SPEAKER_14]: We have a lower skill base than Germany.

979
01:23:42,622 --> 01:23:44,226
[SPEAKER_14]: Why is there a difference?

980
01:23:44,246 --> 01:23:52,847
[SPEAKER_14]: Because successive German governments, almost irrespective of which party it is, have been prepared to invest in their infrastructure and their future.

981
01:23:53,208 --> 01:23:58,221
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we should think about that and improve the economy of our own society.

982
01:23:58,461 --> 01:23:59,584
[SPEAKER_14]: And do you know what?

983
01:23:59,564 --> 01:24:01,827
[SPEAKER_14]: That would lead to better economic growth.

984
01:24:02,107 --> 01:24:04,931
[SPEAKER_14]: It would lead to better opportunities for everybody.

985
01:24:05,171 --> 01:24:08,115
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think this is an offer that's important.

986
01:24:08,436 --> 01:24:14,664
[SPEAKER_14]: And I think it's time that we actually invested in our future rather than presided over our decline.

987
01:24:14,744 --> 01:24:21,893
[SPEAKER_16]: But he's saying, if I understood him, he's saying businesses may scarper under the weight of extra taxation.

988
01:24:21,873 --> 01:24:29,645
[SPEAKER_40]: There's already that issue of uncertainty with Brexit anyway, and we've seen certain companies sort of umming and ahhing and saying, will we stay, will we go?

989
01:24:29,925 --> 01:24:34,352
[SPEAKER_40]: If you say to them, well, you're going to pay more tax when you stay here as well, what's their incentive to stay?

990
01:24:34,592 --> 01:24:42,945
[SPEAKER_14]: Well, actually, the corporation tax level that I'm proposing would actually be less than there is anywhere in the major industrial countries of Western Europe anyway.

991
01:24:43,385 --> 01:24:45,889
[SPEAKER_14]: The crucial thing, and you're right to raise it,

992
01:24:45,869 --> 01:24:52,381
[SPEAKER_14]: has to be gaining tariff-free trade access to the European market as the basis on which they can continue.

993
01:24:52,401 --> 01:24:53,222
[SPEAKER_14]: Because look at it this way.

994
01:24:53,824 --> 01:25:03,962
[SPEAKER_14]: If Airbus are in this country, as they are, they manufacture aircraft parts, they manufacture satellite parts, and the final assembly for the aircraft takes place in Toulouse.

995
01:25:03,942 --> 01:25:10,234
[SPEAKER_14]: some of the parts are made here, some of the engines are made in other places, some parts are made in Spain, that final assembly takes place.

996
01:25:10,535 --> 01:25:15,224
[SPEAKER_14]: If we don't have that tariff-free access to the European market, are they going to stay?

997
01:25:15,505 --> 01:25:16,787
[SPEAKER_14]: Would they want to stay?

998
01:25:17,881 --> 01:25:19,002
[SPEAKER_14]: Ask yourself that question.

999
01:25:19,182 --> 01:25:22,705
[SPEAKER_14]: You could say the same for many other big manufacturing enterprises.

1000
01:25:22,805 --> 01:25:30,432
[SPEAKER_14]: That is why the crucial thing has to be maintaining that economic relationship with Europe outside membership of the European Union.

1001
01:25:30,733 --> 01:25:35,056
[SPEAKER_14]: That is the best way of guaranteeing jobs and a growing manufacturing economy in Britain.

1002
01:25:35,237 --> 01:25:41,783
[SPEAKER_14]: But it will also have a government that is investing alongside them to improve skill levels and improve communications within this country.

1003
01:25:41,803 --> 01:25:42,964
[SPEAKER_16]: A very brief point from you, sir.

1004
01:25:42,984 --> 01:25:44,005
[SPEAKER_16]: Then I will take one last question.

1005
01:25:44,045 --> 01:25:45,226
[SPEAKER_16]: Quickly, if you would.

1006
01:25:45,526 --> 01:25:46,447
[SPEAKER_18]: Security earlier.

1007
01:25:47,608 --> 01:25:47,888
[SPEAKER_18]: Yeah.

1008
01:25:47,868 --> 01:26:00,730
[SPEAKER_18]: A few months ago you said on television that one of the things you would do if you were successful in coming into government was perform a strategic defence review.

1009
01:26:02,448 --> 01:26:06,832
[SPEAKER_18]: Now, they've just gone through a strategic defence review.

1010
01:26:06,852 --> 01:26:08,694
[SPEAKER_18]: Why do we need another one?

1011
01:26:08,714 --> 01:26:11,576
[SPEAKER_14]: Every government that comes into office does a strategic defence review.

1012
01:26:11,997 --> 01:26:14,999
[SPEAKER_14]: There are serious issues about the shortage of ships in the Navy.

1013
01:26:15,280 --> 01:26:17,502
[SPEAKER_14]: There are serious issues about supplies of frigates.

1014
01:26:17,762 --> 01:26:22,626
[SPEAKER_14]: There are serious issues about maritime surveillance aircraft that are not available, that have to be addressed.

1015
01:26:22,646 --> 01:26:27,050
[SPEAKER_14]: There's a crucial issue of cyber security and cyber attacks that are taking place on us.

1016
01:26:27,350 --> 01:26:29,632
[SPEAKER_14]: And there's a crucial issue about terrorist attacks.

1017
01:26:29,652 --> 01:26:32,455
[SPEAKER_14]: And I don't believe you make a society safer

1018
01:26:32,435 --> 01:26:45,018
[SPEAKER_16]: by getting rid of 20,000 police officers as this government has done since 2010.

1019
01:26:45,519 --> 01:26:56,198
[SPEAKER_35]: Is it right to scrap university tuition fees as such an immediate priority when there is so much else that needs doing in terms of living quality for so many people in Britain?

1020
01:26:57,275 --> 01:27:00,858
[SPEAKER_16]: 11 billion it's going to cost, a quarter of your entire spending.

1021
01:27:01,018 --> 01:27:02,820
[SPEAKER_14]: Why university fees?

1022
01:27:03,481 --> 01:27:15,311
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we should invest in education for the future and I do think that abolishing university tuition fees means that any young person has then got the chance to go to university if they can get in.

1023
01:27:15,532 --> 01:27:22,778
[SPEAKER_14]: If you look at the process of applications at the moment, the number of working class students is dropping, the number coming from poorer communities is dropping.

1024
01:27:23,038 --> 01:27:25,581
[SPEAKER_14]: I want to see real access for everybody.

1025
01:27:25,681 --> 01:27:27,062
[SPEAKER_14]: I think that's the right thing to do.

1026
01:27:27,042 --> 01:27:31,166
[SPEAKER_14]: It would not be unusual in many other parts of the world to do this.

1027
01:27:31,186 --> 01:27:35,269
[SPEAKER_14]: Listen, as a young person, basically, I had the offer of free education.

1028
01:27:35,409 --> 01:27:36,170
[SPEAKER_14]: I didn't take it up.

1029
01:27:36,190 --> 01:27:38,732
[SPEAKER_14]: That was my choice, and I'm not complaining about it.

1030
01:27:38,752 --> 01:27:44,177
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't think it's up to me and my generation to pull up the ladder on the generations that are coming behind.

1031
01:27:44,437 --> 01:27:56,948
[SPEAKER_14]: I want to see an education system that really does work for all, so that every child can develop to their full potential, irrespective of their background and the life chances they were given at birth.

1032
01:27:56,928 --> 01:27:58,714
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm sorry, we have to stop you there.

1033
01:27:58,774 --> 01:27:59,939
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you very much indeed.

1034
01:28:00,460 --> 01:28:06,060
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, I've got so much more to say!

1035
01:28:07,289 --> 01:28:12,156
[SPEAKER_16]: That brings us to the end of this edition of Cold Time.

1036
01:28:12,176 --> 01:28:15,721
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you all for coming here to York to put questions to the two party leaders.

1037
01:28:16,202 --> 01:28:22,331
[SPEAKER_16]: We are going to be back on Sunday for our second leader's programme, Nicola Sturgeon of the SNP, Tim Farron of the Liberal Democrats.

1038
01:28:22,652 --> 01:28:25,436
[SPEAKER_16]: That's at five to six on BBC One on Sunday.

1039
01:28:25,816 --> 01:28:28,420
[SPEAKER_16]: Until then, from York, goodnight.

1040
01:28:34,492 --> 01:28:44,890
Oh

